atus/931576779671789568|website=Twitter|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Kids Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite Funny YouTube Creator\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of most subscribed users on YouTube]]\n*[[List of YouTube personalities]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote|Markiplier}}\n*{{youtube|u=markiplierGAME}}\n*{{IMDb name|6290555}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Video games|California}}\n\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American gun control activists]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Let's Players]]\n[[Category:People from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Oahu]]\n[[Category:Revelmode people]]\n[[Category:Video game commentators]]\n[[Category:YouTube Diamond Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:YouTube Gold Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "name_user": "Gamerbob2625", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markiplier"}
{"title_page": "David C. Driskell", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{more footnotes|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:Driskell Woman with Flowers.jpg|thumbnail|Woman with Flowers by David Driskell, 1972]]\n[[File:50th-Loh-Driskell-Henney.jpg|thumbnail|The [[University of Maryland, College Park]] Art Gallery celebrated its 50th anniversary on Feb. 24, 2016, with a memorable art exhibition. Among those attending were President [[Wallace Loh]] and his wife, Barbara, on the left; and Prof. David C. Driskell, along with Prof. [[Dagmar R. Henney]], on the right. Photo courtesy University of Maryland Art Gallery, used with permission.]]\n'''David C. Driskell''' (1931 \u2013 April 1, 2020)<ref name=HistoryMakers>{{cite web|title=ArtMakers : David Driskell|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/david-driskell-40|website=The History Makers|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> was an artist and a scholar in the field of [[African-American art]]. Driskell was [[Emeritus|emeritus professor]] at the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].<ref>http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/</ref>\n\nDriskell was a graduate of Howard University, held a Master of Fine Arts degree from [[The Catholic University of America|Catholic University]] and nine Honorary Doctoral degrees.<ref name=\"neh\" /> In 2000, Driskell was honored by President [[Bill Clinton]] as one of 12 recipients of the [[National Humanities Medal]].\n<ref name= \"neh\">{{cite web|title=AWARDS & HONORS: 2000 NATIONAL HUMANITIES MEDALIST: David C. Driskell|url=http://www.neh.gov/about/awards/national-humanities-medals/david-c-driskell|publisher=National Endowment for the Humanities|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> \n''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar'' by Julie L. McGee, a book detailing Driskell's life and work, was published in 2006.<ref>Julie L. McGee, [https://www.amazon.com/David-C-Driskell-Artist-Scholar/dp/B00BDIO9OQ ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar''], Pomegranate Communications, 2006, {{ISBN|0764937472}}.</ref>\n\nDriskell's art is represented by the DC Moore Gallery.  His first exhibition at the gallery was held in October 2006.<ref name=\"DC Moore Gallery, artist page\">{{cite web|title=DC Moore Gallery, artist page|url=http://www.dcmooregallery.com/artists/david-driskell|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe David C. Driskell Center at the University of Maryland, College Park was named in tribute to him and honors his legacy.<ref>http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/about/index.php</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Eatonton, Georgia]], Driskell died in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]], on April 1, 2020.\n\n==Publications by Driskell==\n* ''Amistad II: Afro-American Art'' (editor), Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1975.\n* ''[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]'', Los Angeles: [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], 1976. {{ISBN|0-87587-070-8}}\n* ''The Afro-American Collection, Fisk University'', with Earl J. Hooks, Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1976.\n* '' Harlem Renaissance: Art of Black America'', introduction by Mary Schmidt Campbell; essays by David Driskell, David Levering Lewis, and [[Deborah Willis (artist)|Deborah Willis Ryan]], New York: [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]], 1987. {{ISBN|0-8109-1099-3}}\n* '' Introspectives: Contemporary Art by Americans and Brazilians of African descent'', curators, Henry J. Drewal and David C. Driskell, Los Angeles: [[California Afro-American Museum]], 1989.\n* ''African American Visual Aesthetics: a Postmodernist View'' (editor) Washington, D.C.: [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institution Press]], 1995. {{ISBN|1-56098-605-0}}\n* ''The Other Side of Color: African American Art in the Collection of [[Camille Olivia Hanks-Cosby|Camille O.]] and [[William H. Cosby, Jr.]]'', San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2001. {{ISBN|0-7649-1455-3}}\n\n==Publications about Driskell==\n* ''David Driskell: a survey: Art Gallery, University of Maryland, College Park, October 21-December 5, 1980'', compiled and edited by Edith A. Tonelli, College Park, MD: [[The Art Gallery at the University of Maryland|University of Maryland Art Gallery]], 1980.\n* Julie L. McGee, ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar'', by San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2006. {{ISBN|0-7649-3747-2}}\n* ''Hidden Heritage: Afro-American Art, 1800-1950'', San Francisco: [[American Alliance of Museums|The Art Museum Association of America]], 1985. {{ISBN|0-930295-03-X}}\n* ''Contemporary Visual Expressions: the Art of [[Sam Gilliam]], [[Martha Jackson-Jarvis]], [[Keith Morrison]], [[William T. Williams]]'', Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution Press, 1987. {{ISBN|0-87474-385-0}}\n* Adrienne L. Childs, ''Evolution: Five Decades of Printmaking by David C. Driskell'', San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-7649-4204-4}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sylvia Snowden]] (studied with Driskell)\n\n==Additional bibliography==\n*David Driskell: [https://web.archive.org/web/20140203020134/http://www.dcmooregallery.com/publications/david-driskell-painting-across-the-decade-1996-2006-2006 ''Painting Across the Decade 1996\u20132006, 2006''] (exhibition catalogue), DC Moore Gallery, 2006\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/index.php The David C. Driskell Center For The Study of The Visual Arts and Culture of African Americans and The African Diaspora]\n*[http://www.visionaryproject.com/driskelldavid David Driskell's oral history video excerpts] at The National Visionary Leadership Project\n*Bridget Goodbody, [http://brooklynrail.org/2012/02/artseen/david-driskell-creative-spirit-five-decades \"DAVID DRISKELL: Creative Spirit: Five Decades\"], ''The Brooklyn Rail'', February 1, 2012\n*[http://www.dcmooregallery.com/artists/david-driskell Artist Page], DC Moore Gallery\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130207023323/http://liveurbanlux.com/prize-fighter/ \"Prize Fighter\"], ''Urban Lux Magazine'', June 2012\n* Eleanor Heartney, [http://images.dcmooregallery.com/www_dcmooregallery_com/David_Driskell_at_DC_Moore.pdf \"David Driskell at DC Moore\"], ''[[Art in American]]'', March 2007\n* Mira Gandy, [http://images.dcmooregallery.com/www_dcmooregallery_com/NYA_FEB_DAVID_C__DRISKELL.pdf \"''Creative Spirit: The Art of David C. Driskell'' exhibit honors artist\u2019s eightieth birthday\"], ''New York Beacon'', February 2, 2012\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driskell, David C.}}\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:American contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Painters from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of America alumni]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{more footnotes|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:Driskell Woman with Flowers.jpg|thumbnail|Woman with Flowers by David Driskell, 1972]]\n[[File:50th-Loh-Driskell-Henney.jpg|thumbnail|The [[University of Maryland, College Park]] Art Gallery celebrated its 50th anniversary on Feb. 24, 2016, with a memorable art exhibition. Among those attending were President [[Wallace Loh]] and his wife, Barbara, on the left; and Prof. David C. Driskell, along with Prof. [[Dagmar R. Henney]], on the right. Photo courtesy University of Maryland Art Gallery, used with permission.]]\n'''David C. Driskell''' (1931 \u2013 April 1, 2020)<ref name=HistoryMakers>{{cite web|title=ArtMakers : David Driskell|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/david-driskell-40|website=The History Makers|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> was an artist and a scholar in the field of [[African-American art]]. Driskell was [[Emeritus|emeritus professor]] at the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].<ref>http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/</ref>\n\nDriskell held a Master of Fine Arts degree from [[The Catholic University of America|Catholic University]] and nine Honorary Doctoral degrees.<ref name=\"neh\" /> In 2000, Driskell was honored by President [[Bill Clinton]] as one of 12 recipients of the [[National Humanities Medal]].\n<ref name= \"neh\">{{cite web|title=AWARDS & HONORS: 2000 NATIONAL HUMANITIES MEDALIST: David C. Driskell|url=http://www.neh.gov/about/awards/national-humanities-medals/david-c-driskell|publisher=National Endowment for the Humanities|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> \n''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar'' by Julie L. McGee, a book detailing Driskell's life and work, was published in 2006.<ref>Julie L. McGee, [https://www.amazon.com/David-C-Driskell-Artist-Scholar/dp/B00BDIO9OQ ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar''], Pomegranate Communications, 2006, {{ISBN|0764937472}}.</ref>\n\nDriskell's art is represented by the DC Moore Gallery.  His first exhibition at the gallery was held in October 2006.<ref name=\"DC Moore Gallery, artist page\">{{cite web|title=DC Moore Gallery, artist page|url=http://www.dcmooregallery.com/artists/david-driskell|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe David C. Driskell Center at the University of Maryland, College Park was named in tribute to him and honors his legacy.<ref>http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/about/index.php</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Eatonton, Georgia]], Driskell died in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]], on April 1, 2020.\n\n==Publications by Driskell==\n* ''Amistad II: Afro-American Art'' (editor), Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1975.\n* ''[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]'', Los Angeles: [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], 1976. {{ISBN|0-87587-070-8}}\n* ''The Afro-American Collection, Fisk University'', with Earl J. Hooks, Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1976.\n* '' Harlem Renaissance: Art of Black America'', introduction by Mary Schmidt Campbell; essays by David Driskell, David Levering Lewis, and [[Deborah Willis (artist)|Deborah Willis Ryan]], New York: [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]], 1987. {{ISBN|0-8109-1099-3}}\n* '' Introspectives: Contemporary Art by Americans and Brazilians of African descent'', curators, Henry J. Drewal and David C. Driskell, Los Angeles: [[California Afro-American Museum]], 1989.\n* ''African American Visual Aesthetics: a Postmodernist View'' (editor) Washington, D.C.: [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institution Press]], 1995. {{ISBN|1-56098-605-0}}\n* ''The Other Side of Color: African American Art in the Collection of [[Camille Olivia Hanks-Cosby|Camille O.]] and [[William H. Cosby, Jr.]]'', San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2001. {{ISBN|0-7649-1455-3}}\n\n==Publications about Driskell==\n* ''David Driskell: a survey: Art Gallery, University of Maryland, College Park, October 21-December 5, 1980'', compiled and edited by Edith A. Tonelli, College Park, MD: [[The Art Gallery at the University of Maryland|University of Maryland Art Gallery]], 1980.\n* Julie L. McGee, ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar'', by San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2006. {{ISBN|0-7649-3747-2}}\n* ''Hidden Heritage: Afro-American Art, 1800-1950'', San Francisco: [[American Alliance of Museums|The Art Museum Association of America]], 1985. {{ISBN|0-930295-03-X}}\n* ''Contemporary Visual Expressions: the Art of [[Sam Gilliam]], [[Martha Jackson-Jarvis]], [[Keith Morrison]], [[William T. Williams]]'', Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution Press, 1987. {{ISBN|0-87474-385-0}}\n* Adrienne L. Childs, ''Evolution: Five Decades of Printmaking by David C. Driskell'', San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-7649-4204-4}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sylvia Snowden]] (studied with Driskell)\n\n==Additional bibliography==\n*David Driskell: [https://web.archive.org/web/20140203020134/http://www.dcmooregallery.com/publications/david-driskell-painting-across-the-decade-1996-2006-2006 ''Painting Across the Decade 1996\u20132006, 2006''] (exhibition catalogue), DC Moore Gallery, 2006\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.driskellcenter.umd.edu/index.php The David C. Driskell Center For The Study of The Visual Arts and Culture of African Americans and The African Diaspora]\n*[http://www.visionaryproject.com/driskelldavid David Driskell's oral history video excerpts] at The National Visionary Leadership Project\n*Bridget Goodbody, [http://brooklynrail.org/2012/02/artseen/david-driskell-creative-spirit-five-decades \"DAVID DRISKELL: Creative Spirit: Five Decades\"], ''The Brooklyn Rail'', February 1, 2012\n*[http://www.dcmooregallery.com/artists/david-driskell Artist Page], DC Moore Gallery\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130207023323/http://liveurbanlux.com/prize-fighter/ \"Prize Fighter\"], ''Urban Lux Magazine'', June 2012\n* Eleanor Heartney, [http://images.dcmooregallery.com/www_dcmooregallery_com/David_Driskell_at_DC_Moore.pdf \"David Driskell at DC Moore\"], ''[[Art in American]]'', March 2007\n* Mira Gandy, [http://images.dcmooregallery.com/www_dcmooregallery_com/NYA_FEB_DAVID_C__DRISKELL.pdf \"''Creative Spirit: The Art of David C. Driskell'' exhibit honors artist\u2019s eightieth birthday\"], ''New York Beacon'', February 2, 2012\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driskell, David C.}}\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:American contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Painters from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of America alumni]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n", "name_user": "DamaniK", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Howard University.  The page included (in the references at the bottom) that he was an Alumnus, but did not mention Howard where he first studied art.  That is a critical omission.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_C._Driskell"}
