{"title_page": "Muflih al-Turki", "text_new": "'''Muflih al-Turki''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0641\u0644\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a}}, died April 2, 872) was a [[Turkic peoples|Turkish]] military officer of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in the mid-9th century. He played a prominent role in the events known as the [[Anarchy at Samarra]] and was later killed in battle against the [[Zanj Rebellion|Zanj]] rebels of southern [[Iraq]].\n\n== Career ==\nMuflih was a close associate of the general [[Musa ibn Bugha al-Kabir]], possibly serving as his chief lieutenant.{{sfn|Gordon|2001|p=237 n. 108}} He is first mentioned by the chronicler [[al-Tabari]] during the [[Abbasid civil war (865\u2013866)|civil war of 865\u2013866]], in which he was a member of the army that besieged [[Baghdad]].{{sfn|Saliba|1985|p=86}} After the war, he followed Musa to [[Jibal]] when the latter was appointed governor there in 867. During his time in Jibal he served as Musa's second in command and undertook several military expeditions, defeating the [[Dulafid dynasty|Dulafid]] ruler [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abu Dulaf]] near [[Hamedan|Hamadhan]] and [[Karaj|al-Karaj]]{{sfn|Saliba|1985|pp=145-146}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=189}} and attacking the inhabitants of [[Qom|Qumm]].{{sfn|Saliba|1985|pp=154-155}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=196}}\n\nIn 869, Muflih entered the province of [[Tabaristan]], which was controlled by the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Zaydid]] rebel [[al-Hasan ibn Zayd]]. He was able to defeat al-Hasan and occupy both [[Sari, Iran|Sari]] and [[Amol|Amul]]. He then set out for the region of [[Daylam]], where al-Hasan had fled to,{{sfn|Ibn Isfandiyar|1905|pp=179-180}}{{sfn|Saliba|1985|p=156}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=204-205}} but he was recalled en route by Musa, who had decided to depart for the capital [[Abbasid Samarra|Samarra]]. He therefore abandoned Tabaristan, allowing al-Hasan to restore his rule there.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=24-26}}{{sfn|Ibn Isfandiyar|1905|p=180}}\n\nFollowing their return to Samarra, Muflih was an important supporter of Musa during the short reign of the caliph [[al-Muhtadi]] ({{reign|869|870}}).{{sfn|Kennedy|2001|p=150}} He participated in the downfall of the rival general [[Salih ibn Wasif]] and was thought to be involved in a plot to depose the caliph.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=69, 71, 73, 79, 82, 86-87, 89-90}}  In 870 Musa, Muflih and [[Bayakbak]] departed for [[Upper Mesopotamia]], where they fought the [[Kharijite]] rebel leader [[Kharijite Rebellion (866\u2013896)|Musawir]] and forced him to flee.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=90-91}} While in Upper Mesopotamia, Musa and Muflih learned that al-Muhtadi was plotting to relieve them of their commands and have them arrested or killed, so they abandoned the campaign and advanced toward Samarra with their troops. During the resulting crisis, al-Muhtadi was deposed and killed, and the two commanders were able to return to the capital.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=99 ff.}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=220-223}}\n\nShortly after the ascension of [[al-Mu'tamid]] ({{reign|870|892}}), Muflih returned to al-Jazira to fight Musawir; he succeeded in forcing the rebel to temporarily abandon [[Hdatta|al-Haditha]], but was unable to kill or capture him and eventually returned to Samarra.{{sfn|Waines|1992|p=116}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=219-220}} Around the beginning of 872 he headed for [[Tikrit|Takrit]], where he fought some Arab tribesmen that were reportedly sympathetic to Musawir.{{sfn|Waines|1992|p=136}}\n\nIn February 872 Muflih and the caliph's brother [[Al-Muwaffaq|Abu Ahmad ibn al-Mutawakkil]] decided to undertake a campaign against the Zanj and set out for [[Basra]]. On April 1 they engaged the Zanj in the vicinity of the [[Nahr Abi al-Khasib|Abu al-Khasib Canal]], but Muflih was mortally wounded by an arrow that struck him in the temple, and the government army was routed. Muflih died of his wound on the following morning, after which his body was taken to Samarra and buried there.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=137, 139-42}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|p=236}}{{sfn|Al-Mas'udi|1874|pp=39-40}} Following his death, his son [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Muflih|Abd al-Rahman]] seems to have assumed his position as one of Musa's chief officers.{{sfn|Gordon|2001|pp=252-253 n. 41}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Gordon-The Breaking of a Thousand Swords}}\n* {{cite book | last = Ibn al-Athir | first = 'Izz al-Din | authorlink = Ali ibn al-Athir | title = Al-Kamil fi al-Tarikh, Vol. 6. | publisher = Dar al-'Ilmiyyah | language = Arabic | location = Beirut | year = 1987 | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Ibn Isfandiyar | first = Muhammad ibn al-Hasan | authorlink = Ibn Isfandiyar | title = An Abridged Translation of the History of Tabaristan, Compiled About A.H. 613 (A.D. 1216). | others = Trans. Edward G. Browne. | publisher = E.J. Brill | location = Leyden | year = 1905 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HhNgAAAAMAAJ | ref=harv}}\n* {{Kennedy-The Armies of the Caliphs}}\n* {{cite book | last = Al-Mas'udi | first = Ali ibn al-Husain | authorlink = Al-Masudi | title = Les Prairies D'Or, Tome Huitieme. | others = Trans. C. Barbier de Meynard | publisher = Imprimerie Nationale | language = French | location = Paris | year = 1874 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XjhbAAAAQAAJ | ref=harv}}\n* {{The History of al-Tabari | volume = 35 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3STT4w-sjdgC}}\n* {{The History of al-Tabari | volume = 36 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-ctgf6WSCPMC}}\n\n[[Category:872 deaths]]\n[[Category:Generals of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:9th-century Turkic people]]\n[[Category:Deaths by arrow wounds]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Muflih al-Turki''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0641\u0644\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a}}, died April 2, 872) was a [[Turkic peoples|Turkish]] military officer of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in the mid-9th century. He played a prominent role in the events known as the [[Anarchy at Samarra]] and was later killed in battle against the [[Zanj Rebellion|Zanj]] rebels of southern [[Iraq]].\n\n== Career ==\nMuflih was a close associate of the general [[Musa ibn Bugha al-Kabir]], possibly serving as his chief lieutenant.{{sfn|Gordon|2001|p=237 n. 108}} He is first mentioned by the chronicler [[al-Tabari]] during the [[Abbasid civil war (865\u2013866)|civil war of 865\u2013866]], in which he was a member of the army that besieged [[Baghdad]].{{sfn|Saliba|1985|p=86}} After the war, he followed Musa to [[Jibal]] when the latter was appointed governor there in 867. During his time in Jibal he served as Musa's second in command and undertook several military expeditions, defeating the [[Dulafid dynasty|Dulafid]] ruler [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abu Dulaf]] near [[Hamedan|Hamadhan]] and [[Karaj|al-Karaj]]{{sfn|Saliba|1985|pp=145-146}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=189}} and attacking the inhabitants of [[Qom|Qumm]].{{sfn|Saliba|1985|pp=154-155}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=196}}\n\nIn 869, Muflih entered the province of [[Tabaristan]], which was controlled by the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Zaydid]] rebel [[al-Hasan ibn Zayd]]. He was able to defeat al-Hasan and occupy both [[Sari, Iran|Sari]] and [[Amol|Amul]]. He then set out for the region of [[Daylam]], where al-Hasan had fled to,{{sfn|Ibn Isfandiyar|1905|pp=179-180}}{{sfn|Saliba|1985|p=156}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=204-205}} but he was recalled en route by Musa, who had decided to depart for the capital [[Abbasid Samarra|Samarra]]. He therefore abandoned Tabaristan, allowing al-Hasan to restore his rule there.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=24-26}}{{sfn|Ibn Isfandiyar|1905|p=180}}\n\nFollowing their return to Samarra, Muflih was an important supporter of Musa during the short reign of the caliph [[al-Muhtadi]] ({{reign|869|870}}).{{sfn|Kennedy|2001|p=150}} He participated in the downfall of the rival general [[Salih ibn Wasif]] and was thought to be involved in a plot to depose the caliph.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=69, 71, 73, 79, 82, 86-87, 89-90}}  In 870 Musa, Muflih and [[Bayakbak]] departed for [[Upper Mesopotamia]], where they fought the [[Kharijite]] rebel leader [[Kharijite Rebellion (866\u2013896)|Musawir]] and forced him to flee.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=90-91}} While in Upper Mesopotamia, Musa and Muflih learned that al-Muhtadi was plotting to relieve them of their commands and have them arrested or killed, so they abandoned the campaign and advanced toward Samarra with their troops. During the resulting crisis, al-Muhtadi was deposed and killed, and the two commanders were able to return to the capital.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=99 ff.}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=220-223}}\n\nShortly after the ascension of [[al-Mu'tamid]] ({{reign|870|892}}), Muflih returned to al-Jazira to fight Musawir; he succeeded in forcing the rebel to temporarily abandon [[Hdatta|al-Haditha]], but was unable to kill or capture him and eventually returned to Samarra.{{sfn|Waines|1992|p=116}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|pp=219-220}} Around the beginning of 872 he headed for [[Tikrit|Takrit]], where he fought some Arab tribesmen that were reportedly sympathetic to Musawir.{{sfn|Waines|1992|p=136}}\n\nIn February 872 Muflih and the caliph's brother [[Al-Muwaffaq|Abu Ahmad ibn al-Mutawakkil]] decided to undertake a campaign against the Zanj and set out for [[Basra]]. On April 1 they engaged the Zanj in the vicinity of the [[Nahr Abi al-Khasib|Abu al-Khasib Canal]], but Muflih was mortally wounded by an arrow that struck him in the temple, and the government army was routed. Muflih died of his wound on the following morning, after which his body was taken to Samarra and buried there.{{sfn|Waines|1992|pp=137, 139-42}}{{sfn|Ibn al-Athir|1987|p=236}}{{sfn|Al-Mas'udi|1874|pp=39-40}} Following his death, his son [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Muflih|Abd al-Rahman]] seems to have assumed his position as one of Musa's chief officers.{{sfn|Gordon|2001|pp=252-253 n. 41}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Gordon-The Breaking of a Thousand Swords}}\n* {{cite book | last = Ibn al-Athir | first = 'Izz al-Din | authorlink = Ali ibn al-Athir | title = Al-Kamil fi al-Tarikh, Vol. 6. | publisher = Dar al-'Ilmiyyah | language = Arabic | location = Beirut | year = 1987 | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Ibn Isfandiyar | first = Muhammad ibn al-Hasan | authorlink = Ibn Isfandiyar | title = An Abridged Translation of the History of Tabaristan, Compiled About A.H. 613 (A.D. 1216). | others = Trans. Edward G. Browne. | publisher = E.J. Brill | location = Leyden | year = 1905 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HhNgAAAAMAAJ | ref=harv}}\n* {{Kennedy-The Armies of the Caliphs}}\n* {{cite book | last = Al-Mas'udi | first = Ali ibn al-Husain | authorlink = Al-Masudi | title = Les Prairies D'Or, Tome Huitieme. | others = Trans. C. Barbier de Meynard | publisher = Imprimerie Nationale | language = French | location = Paris | year = 1874 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XjhbAAAAQAAJ | ref=harv}}\n* {{The History of al-Tabari | volume = 35 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3STT4w-sjdgC}}\n* {{The History of al-Tabari | volume = 36 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-ctgf6WSCPMC}}\n\n[[Category:872 deaths]]\n[[Category:Generals of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:9th-century Turkic people]]\n[[Category:Deaths by arrow wounds]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Ro4444", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 948669694 byGiantSnowman(talk); unwarranted revision of date formats)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muflih_al-Turki"}
{"title_page": "Sean Russo", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Sean Russo\n| image          = Xxxx10 - Sean Russo swimming - 3b - 2010 IPC Swimming World Championships photo.jpg \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = Russo at the 2010 IPC Swimming World Championships, where he won a bronze medal in the 100m backstroke\n| fullname       = Sean Russo\n| nicknames      = \n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| classification = [[S13 (classification)|S13, SB13, SM13]]\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]], [[backstroke]]\n| club           = \n| coach          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1991|4|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         =\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[paralympic swimming]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[IPC Swimming World Championships|World Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | {{nowrap|[[2010 IPC Swimming World Championships|2010 Eindhoven]]}} | {{nowrap|100 m backstroke S13}}}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|{{nowrap|100 m backstroke S13}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Sean Russo''' (born 5 April 1991) is an Australian swimmer.  He represented Australia at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] and [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref name=\"swim2016\">{{cite web|title=Swimming Australia Paralympic Squad Announcement|url=http://www.swimming.org.au/NewsCentral/Swimming-Australia-Paralympic-Squad-Announcement.aspx|website=Swimming Australia News|accessdate=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113144330/http://www.swimming.org.au/NewsCentral/Swimming-Australia-Paralympic-Squad-Announcement.aspx|archive-date=13 November 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nRusso was born on 5 April 1991 and has [[retinitis pigmentosa]].<ref name=apc/>  As a child, he also had [[asthma]].<ref name=apc/> He resides in [[Revesby, New South Wales]].<ref name=\"nswfrom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/the-express/revesbys-russo-swimming-for-gold-at-2016-paralympics-in-rio/news-story/bf1463547e19b473fc1f5baa5c0397d7|title=Revesby\u2019s Russo swimming for gold at 2016 Paralympics in Rio|last=Buckley|first=Danielle|date=|website=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref> In 2017, he is currently completing a Certificate III and Certificate IV of Dental Assisting.\n\n==Swimming==\n[[File:310812 - Sean Russo - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (01).JPG|left|thumb|300x300px|Russo at the 2012 London Paralympics]]\nRusso is an [[S13 (classification)|S13 classified]] swimmer.<ref name=\"apc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/sean-russo |title=Sean Russo |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |location=Australia |year=2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"abcstuff\" /><ref name=\"teamrevealed\" /> He started competing in swimming in 1995 as a result of asthma.<ref name=\"apc\" />  He made his national team debut in 2010 at the IPC Swimming World Championships, competing in the 100m backstroke where he earned a bronze medal.  At the event, he also set Australian records in the 100m freestyle and 100m butterfly events.<ref name=\"apc\" />\n\nHe was a member of the Australian team competing at the Dutch hosted 2011 IPC World Swimming Championships.<ref name=\"youngestyo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ascta.com/news/index.cfm?fuseaction=display_main&NewsID=14509&orgid=3429&dts=58201041735 |title=Australian Swimming Coaches and Teachers Association |publisher=Australian Swimming Coaches and Teachers Association |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130102014320/http://www.ascta.com/news/index.cfm?fuseaction=display_main&NewsID=14509&orgid=3429&dts=58201041735 |archivedate=2 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Finishing with a personal best time of 1:02.52 in the men's 100m backstroke, he earned a silver medal.<ref name=\"abcstuff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-08-21/cowdrey-leek-finish-with-world-records/952544 |title=Cowdrey, Leek finish with world records |publisher=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=2010-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n[[File:310812 - Sean Russo - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (02).JPG|thumb]]\nAt the 2012 Australian national championships, he finished first in the men's 50m backstroke multi-disability event.<ref name=\"nswfrom\" /> He was selected to represent [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in swimming<ref name=\"teamrevealed\">{{cite web |url=http://paralympic.org.au/news/paralympic-swim-team-revealed |title=Paralympic swim team revealed |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |date=2012-07-10 |accessdate=2012-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711022235/http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/paralympic-swim-team-revealed |archivedate=11 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"abc2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-07-10/cowdrey-leads-paralympic-swim-team/4121704?section=sport |title=Cowdrey leads Paralympic swim team - ABC Grandstand Sport - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  in seven events: the Men's 100 m Backstroke S13, 100 m Breaststroke SB13, 100 m Butterfly S13, 100 m Freestyle S13, 200 m Individual Medley SM13, 400 m Freestyle S13 and 50 m Freestyle S13.<ref name=\"IPC\">{{IPC profile|surname=Russo|givenname=Sean}}. Retrieved 6 October 2012.</ref> He set an Oceania Record in the 100 m Backstroke S13.<ref name=\"Oceanian Records\">{{cite web|title=Oceanian Records|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Results/regional-records/Oceania/Swimming|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships]] in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], he won a bronze medal in Men's 100 m Backstroke S13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aussies add two silver and two bronze on Day 3 in Glasgow|url=http://www.swimming.org.au/article.php?group_id=76886&id=2|website=Swimming Australia News, 16 July 2015|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> He finished fifth in the Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, seventh in the Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13 and ninth in the Men's 400m Freestyle S13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sean Russo results|url=http://www.paralympic.org/glasgow-2015/schedule-results|website=Glasgow 2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he is a [[New South Institute of Sport]] scholarship holder.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 swimming scholarships|url=http://www.nswis.com.au/assets/documents/Scholarship%20Holders%20-%20Swimming%20July%202015.pdf|website=New South Wales Institute of Sport|accessdate=16 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304145648/http://www.nswis.com.au/assets/documents/Scholarship%20Holders%20-%20Swimming%20July%202015.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRusso competed at the [[2016 Rio Paralympics]] and competed in six events. He placed seventh in Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, fifth in the Men's 100m Backstroke S13 and sixth in Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13. He also competed in Men's 50m Freestyle S13, Men's 100m Freestyle S13 and Men's 100m Butterfly S13 but didn't progress to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sean Russo|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/sean-russo|website=Rio Paralympics Official Results|publisher=Rio 2016 Paralympics|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/sean-russo/ Sean Russo] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|id=sean-russo|old_id=870696}}\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{2012 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russo, Sean}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male Paralympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:S13-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Sean Russo\n| image          = Xxxx10 - Sean Russo swimming - 3b - 2010 IPC Swimming World Championships photo.jpg \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = Russo at the 2010 IPC Swimming World Championships, where he won a bronze medal in the 100m backstroke\n| fullname       = Sean Russo\n| nicknames      = \n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| classification = [[S13 (classification)|S13, SB13, SM13]]\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]], [[backstroke]]\n| club           = \n| coach          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1991|4|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         =\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[paralympic swimming]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[IPC Swimming World Championships|World Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | {{nowrap|[[2010 IPC Swimming World Championships|2010 Eindhoven]]}} | {{nowrap|100 m backstroke S13}}}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|2015 Glasgow]]|{{nowrap|100 m backstroke S13}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Sean Russo''' (born 5 April 1991) is an Australian swimmer.  He represented Australia at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] and [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref name=\"swim2016\">{{cite web|title=Swimming Australia Paralympic Squad Announcement|url=http://www.swimming.org.au/NewsCentral/Swimming-Australia-Paralympic-Squad-Announcement.aspx|website=Swimming Australia News|accessdate=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113144330/http://www.swimming.org.au/NewsCentral/Swimming-Australia-Paralympic-Squad-Announcement.aspx|archive-date=13 November 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nRusso was born on 5 April 1991 and has [[retinitis pigmentosa]].<ref name=apc/>  As a child, he also had [[asthma]].<ref name=apc/> He resides in [[Revesby, New South Wales]].<ref name=\"nswfrom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/the-express/revesbys-russo-swimming-for-gold-at-2016-paralympics-in-rio/news-story/bf1463547e19b473fc1f5baa5c0397d7|title=Revesby\u2019s Russo swimming for gold at 2016 Paralympics in Rio|last=Buckley|first=Danielle|date=|website=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref> In 2017, he is currently completing a Certificate III and Certificate IV of Dental Assisting.\n\n==Swimming==\n[[File:310812 - Sean Russo - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (01).JPG|left|thumb|300x300px|Russo at the 2012 London Paralympics]]\nRusso is an [[S13 (classification)|S13 classified]] swimmer.<ref name=\"apc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/sean-russo |title=Sean Russo |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |location=Australia |year=2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"abcstuff\" /><ref name=\"teamrevealed\" /> He started competing in swimming in 1995 as a result of asthma.<ref name=\"apc\" />  He made his national team debut in 2010 at the IPC Swimming World Championships, competing in the 100m backstroke where he earned a bronze medal.  At the event, he also set Australian records in the 100m freestyle and 100m butterfly events.<ref name=\"apc\" />\n\nHe was a member of the Australian team competing at the Dutch hosted 2011 IPC World Swimming Championships.<ref name=\"youngestyo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ascta.com/news/index.cfm?fuseaction=display_main&NewsID=14509&orgid=3429&dts=58201041735 |title=Australian Swimming Coaches and Teachers Association |publisher=Australian Swimming Coaches and Teachers Association |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130102014320/http://www.ascta.com/news/index.cfm?fuseaction=display_main&NewsID=14509&orgid=3429&dts=58201041735 |archivedate=2 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Finishing with a personal best time of 1:02.52 in the men's 100m backstroke, he earned a silver medal.<ref name=\"abcstuff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-08-21/cowdrey-leek-finish-with-world-records/952544 |title=Cowdrey, Leek finish with world records |publisher=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=2010-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n[[File:310812 - Sean Russo - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (02).JPG|thumb]]\nAt the 2012 Australian national championships, he finished first in the men's 50m backstroke multi-disability event.<ref name=\"nswfrom\" /> He was selected to represent [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in swimming<ref name=\"teamrevealed\">{{cite web |url=http://paralympic.org.au/news/paralympic-swim-team-revealed |title=Paralympic swim team revealed |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |date=2012-07-10 |accessdate=2012-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711022235/http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/paralympic-swim-team-revealed |archivedate=11 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"abc2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-07-10/cowdrey-leads-paralympic-swim-team/4121704?section=sport |title=Cowdrey leads Paralympic swim team - ABC Grandstand Sport - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>  in seven events: the Men's 100 m Backstroke S13, 100 m Breaststroke SB13, 100 m Butterfly S13, 100 m Freestyle S13, 200 m Individual Medley SM13, 400 m Freestyle S13 and 50 m Freestyle S13.<ref name=\"IPC\">{{IPC profile|surname=Russo|givenname=Sean}}. Retrieved 6 October 2012.</ref> He set an Oceania Record in the 100 m Backstroke S13.<ref name=\"Oceanian Records\">{{cite web|title=Oceanian Records|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Results/regional-records/Oceania/Swimming|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships]] in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], he won a bronze medal in Men's 100 m Backstroke S13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aussies add two silver and two bronze on Day 3 in Glasgow|url=http://www.swimming.org.au/article.php?group_id=76886&id=2|website=Swimming Australia News, 16 July 2015|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> He finished fifth in the Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, seventh in the Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13 and ninth in the Men's 400m Freestyle S13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sean Russo results|url=http://www.paralympic.org/glasgow-2015/schedule-results|website=Glasgow 2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he is a [[New South Institute of Sport]] scholarship holder.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 swimming scholarships|url=http://www.nswis.com.au/assets/documents/Scholarship%20Holders%20-%20Swimming%20July%202015.pdf|website=New South Wales Institute of Sport|accessdate=16 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304145648/http://www.nswis.com.au/assets/documents/Scholarship%20Holders%20-%20Swimming%20July%202015.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRusso competed at the [[2016 Rio Paralympics]] and competed in six events. He placed seventh in Men's 100m Breaststroke SB13, fifth in the Men's 100m Backstroke S13 and sixth in Men's 200m Individual Medley SM13. He also competed in Men's 50m Freestyle S13, Men's 100m Freestyle S13 and Men's 100m Butterfly S13 but didn't progress to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sean Russo|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/sean-russo|website=Rio Paralympics Official Results|publisher=Rio 2016 Paralympics|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/sean-russo/ Sean Russo] at the [[Australian Paralympic Committee]]\n* {{IPC athlete|870696}}\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{2012 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russo, Sean}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male Paralympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:S13-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sean_Russo"}
{"title_page": "Dan Pe\u00f1a", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image              = Dan at Guthrie Castle (Graduation Night).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Daniel Steven Pe\u00f1a\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1945|8|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cuntsville, Florida]], [[United States|USA]]\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| education          = San Fernando Valley State College (now [[CSUN]]) {{small|(BS)}}\n| occupation         = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| title              = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| website            = [http://www.danpena.co.uk danpena.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Steven Pe\u00f1a Sr.''' <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/_DlggeBNaJSGMvRdTPvXVNoC740/appointments |title=Daniel Steven Pena - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |language=en|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref> (born August 10, 1945, a.k.a. Dan Pe\u00f1a), is an American businessman. He resides at [[Guthrie Castle]] in [[Scotland]], in which he previously operated a wedding business.<ref name=castle>{{cite news |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/scotland/Rescued-castle-to-open-its.2449274.jp |title=Rescued castle to open its doors |last=Urqurhart |first=Frank |date=4 August 2003 |work=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\nHe received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in Business Administration from San Fernando Valley State College (now [[California State University, Northridge]]) in 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYwYGBFs-iI |title=Dan Pena's Commencement Speech at the California State University, Northridge|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPe\u00f1a was the founder and chairman of The Guthrie Group,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jerseyfsc.org/registry/documentsearch/NameDetail.aspx?id=45270 |title=GUTHRIE GROUP (C.I.) LIMITED|website=[[Jersey Financial Services Commission|JFSC]] Companies Registry}}</ref> an investment consortium, incorporated in [[Jersey]] in 2002 and dissolved in 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Daniel S. Sr.}}\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:California State University, Northridge alumni]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Life coaches]]\n[[Category:Personal development]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image              = Dan at Guthrie Castle (Graduation Night).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Daniel Steven Pe\u00f1a\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1945|8|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], [[United States|USA]]\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| education          = San Fernando Valley State College (now [[CSUN]]) {{small|(BS)}}\n| occupation         = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| title              = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| website            = [http://www.danpena.co.uk danpena.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Steven Pe\u00f1a Sr.''' <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/_DlggeBNaJSGMvRdTPvXVNoC740/appointments |title=Daniel Steven Pena - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House) |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |language=en|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref> (born August 10, 1945, a.k.a. Dan Pe\u00f1a), is an American businessman. He resides at [[Guthrie Castle]] in [[Scotland]], in which he previously operated a wedding business.<ref name=castle>{{cite news |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/scotland/Rescued-castle-to-open-its.2449274.jp |title=Rescued castle to open its doors |last=Urqurhart |first=Frank |date=4 August 2003 |work=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\nHe received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in Business Administration from San Fernando Valley State College (now [[California State University, Northridge]]) in 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYwYGBFs-iI |title=Dan Pena's Commencement Speech at the California State University, Northridge|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPe\u00f1a was the founder and chairman of The Guthrie Group,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jerseyfsc.org/registry/documentsearch/NameDetail.aspx?id=45270 |title=GUTHRIE GROUP (C.I.) LIMITED|website=[[Jersey Financial Services Commission|JFSC]] Companies Registry}}</ref> an investment consortium, incorporated in [[Jersey]] in 2002 and dissolved in 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Daniel S. Sr.}}\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:California State University, Northridge alumni]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Life coaches]]\n[[Category:Personal development]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "82.7.151.170", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Pe%C3%B1a"}
{"title_page": "Archie Mountbatten-Windsor", "text_new": "{{short description|Only child of the Duke and Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}} \n<!-- Do not change to 'Infobox royalty'. -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Archie Mountbatten-Windsor\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2019|05|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Portland Hospital]], London, United Kingdom<!--Sovereign country should be used here. See Talk:Archie Mountbatten-Windsor#Country of birth--><!--Do not link city or country per MOS:OVERLINK-->\n| nationality        = {{ubl|[[British nationality law|United Kingdom]]|[[United States nationality law|United States]]}}\n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]] \n* [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]] <!--maiden name should be used here--> }}\n| relatives          = {{plainlist|\n* [[British royal family]]\n* [[Family of Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]] \n* [[House of Windsor]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor''' (born 6 May 2019) is the son of [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]]. A great-grandchild of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], he is seventh in the [[line of succession to the British throne]].\n\n==Birth and family==\nArchie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor is the son of the [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Duke]] and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|Duchess of Sussex]]. He was born at 05:26 [[British Summer Time|BST]] (04:26 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on 6 May 2019 at the [[Portland Hospital]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48178229|title=Royal baby: Meghan gives birth to boy, Harry announces|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/05/17/meghan-markle-gave-birth-private-portland-hospital-westminster/|title=Duchess of Sussex gave birth at Portland Hospital in Westminster, royal baby's birth certificate confirms|first=Gareth|last=Davies|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 May 2019|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> Several landmarks were illuminated in different colours to mark the birth, including [[Niagara Falls]], the [[CN Tower]] and the [[London Eye]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/falls-royal-birth-blue-1.5125083|title=Niagara Falls will shine blue Monday to mark royal birth|work=[[CBC News]]|first=Justin|last=Mowat|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/cn-tower-purple-royal-baby-1.5125275|title=CN Tower lit in purple to mark birth of royal baby|work=[[CBC News]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Press Association]]|url=https://home.bt.com/news/uk-news/london-eye-to-turn-red-white-and-blue-for-royal-baby-11364360245841|title=London Eye to turn red, white and blue for royal baby|work=[[BT Group|BT]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> His name was announced on 8 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48201625 |title=Royal baby: Duke and Duchess of Sussex name son Archie |work=[[BBC News]] |date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> He was [[baptised]], wearing the [[royal christening gown#United Kingdom|royal christening gown]], by the [[Justin Welby|Archbishop of Canterbury]] on 6 July 2019 in the Private Chapel of [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48891808|title=Harry and Meghan's baby Archie christened at Windsor|date=6 July 2019|last=Dymond|first=Jonny|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nArchie Mountbatten-Windsor is descended from the [[British royal family]] on his father's side and from the American [[American working class|working]] and [[American middle class|middle class]]es on [[Family of Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|his mother's side]].<ref>{{cite news| quote=Doria was born and raised in a middle-class African-American community of Los Angeles. She later earned a master\u2019s degree in social work from the University of Southern California and became a yoga instructor.|last1=Carroll |first1=Leslie |title=How Meghan Markle Was Destined for the Spotlight |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/how-meghan-markle-was-destined-for-the-spotlight |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| quote=She had a pretty American upper middle class existence, including a private elementary and secondary school education and an undergraduate degree from an elite American university.|last1=McFadden |first1=Syreeta |title=Meghan Markle is no modern-day Cinderella. She's better. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/meghan-markle-no-modern-day-cinderella-she-s-better-ncna824596 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Barry\">{{cite news|quote=... he represents change for the oldest of houses. He is half American, descended on his mother\u2019s side from a bellhop in a Cleveland hotel, a laundry worker in Chattanooga, and a bartender in an Atlanta saloon. |last1=Barry |first1=Ellen |last2=Karasz |first2=Palko |title=Meghan, Duchess of Sussex, Gives Birth to a Boy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/world/europe/meghan-markle-baby-boy.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> He is a citizen both [[citizen of the United Kingdom|of the United Kingdom]] and [[Citizenship of the United States|of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|title=US tax authorities could stake a claim to Baby Sussex's inheritance|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/07/us-tax-authorities-could-stake-claim-baby-sussexs-inheritance/|first=Harriet|last=Alexander|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=7 May 2019|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news ||title=Royal baby: All you need to know about the birth of Harry and Meghan's child |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47934729 |accessdate=6 May 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Title and succession==\nA great-grandchild of [[Queen Elizabeth II]],<ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/06/meghan-duchess-of-sussex-gives-birth-to-boy|title=Royal baby: Meghan, Duchess of Sussex, gives birth to boy |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> Archie Mountbatten-Windsor is seventh in the [[Succession to the British throne|line of succession to the British throne]].<ref name=\"Barry\" /> He is also [[heir apparent]] to his father's [[Dukedom of Sussex]], [[Earl of Dumbarton|Earldom of Dumbarton]], and [[Baron Kilkeel|Barony of Kilkeel]].<ref name=\"guard\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/05/06/royal-baby-meghan-markle-birth-boy-latest-live-news-updates/|title=Royal baby: Prince Harry says birth of son is 'the most amazing experience' as world waits for first sighting|last1=Furness|first1=Hannah|date=6 May 2019|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=7 May 2019|last2=Southworth|first2=Phoebe|last3=Herbert|first3=Samantha}}</ref> \n\nAs Harry is not the eldest son of the Prince of Wales, his son is neither a [[British prince]] nor does he have the style Royal Highness. However, if and when Prince Charles becomes King, according to Letters Patent issued by George V in 1917, Harry's son, as the son of the son of the sovereign will have the right to the title of Prince and style of Royal Highness (although there is precedent for titles and styles of this nature to not be used, as in the case of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex#Issue|Prince Edward's children]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Royal Titles: HRH and Prince/Princess |url=https://royalcentral.co.uk/features/history-blogs/history-of-royal-titles-hrh-and-princeprincess-2064/ |website=Royal Central |date=18 May 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> There was the option of using Prince Harry's [[subsidiary title]] of Earl of Dumbarton, as a [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy]], but Meghan and Harry decided instead that he would be styled as [[Master (form of address)#Current usage in the United Kingdom|Master]] Archie Mountbatten-Windsor,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48204592|title=Archie Harrison: The meaning behind the royal baby's name|publisher=[[BBC News]]|first=|last=|date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/succession|title=Succession|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=17 May 2019|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> in accordance with their wish that he grow up as a private citizen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/world/europe/royal-baby-sussex.html|title=Harry and Meghan Name Their Son: Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Ellen|last=Barry|date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor \u2013 what's in a name? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/08/archie-harrison-mountbatten-windsor-whats-in-a-name-royal-baby |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 May 2019|accessdate=11 May 2019|author= Davies, Caroline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.royal.uk/archie-harrison-mountbatten-windsor Archie Mountbatten-Windsor] at the Royal Family website\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou||6 May|2019|||}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|The Duke of Sussex]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Succession to the British throne]]|years=7th in line}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|The Duke of York]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex}}\n{{Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mountbatten-Windsor, Archie}}\n\n[[Category:2019 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of British descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British people]]\n[[Category:American children]]\n[[Category:British children]]\n[[Category:British people of African-American descent]]\n[[Category:Children of peers and peeresses]]\n[[Category:Markle family]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family|Archie Mountbatten-Windsor]]\n[[Category:People from London]]\n[[Category:Royal children]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Only child of the Duke and Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}} \n<!-- Do not change to 'Infobox royalty'. -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Archie Mountbatten-Windsor\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2019|05|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Portland Hospital]], London, United Kingdom<!--Sovereign country should be used here. See Talk:Archie Mountbatten-Windsor#Country of birth--><!--Do not link city or country per MOS:OVERLINK-->\n| nationality        = {{ubl|[[British nationality law|United Kingdom]]|[[United States nationality law|United States]]}}\n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]] \n* [[Meghan Markle]] <!--maiden name should be used here--> }}\n| relatives          = {{plainlist|\n* [[British royal family]]\n* [[Family of Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|Markle family]] \n* [[House of Windsor]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor''' (born 6 May 2019) is the son of [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]]. A great-grandchild of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], he is seventh in the [[line of succession to the British throne]].\n\n==Birth and family==\nArchie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor is the son of the [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Duke]] and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|Duchess of Sussex]]. He was born at 05:26 [[British Summer Time|BST]] (04:26 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on 6 May 2019 at the [[Portland Hospital]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48178229|title=Royal baby: Meghan gives birth to boy, Harry announces|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/05/17/meghan-markle-gave-birth-private-portland-hospital-westminster/|title=Duchess of Sussex gave birth at Portland Hospital in Westminster, royal baby's birth certificate confirms|first=Gareth|last=Davies|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 May 2019|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> Several landmarks were illuminated in different colours to mark the birth, including [[Niagara Falls]], the [[CN Tower]] and the [[London Eye]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/falls-royal-birth-blue-1.5125083|title=Niagara Falls will shine blue Monday to mark royal birth|work=[[CBC News]]|first=Justin|last=Mowat|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/cn-tower-purple-royal-baby-1.5125275|title=CN Tower lit in purple to mark birth of royal baby|work=[[CBC News]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Press Association]]|url=https://home.bt.com/news/uk-news/london-eye-to-turn-red-white-and-blue-for-royal-baby-11364360245841|title=London Eye to turn red, white and blue for royal baby|work=[[BT Group|BT]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> His name was announced on 8 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48201625 |title=Royal baby: Duke and Duchess of Sussex name son Archie |work=[[BBC News]] |date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> He was [[baptised]], wearing the [[royal christening gown#United Kingdom|royal christening gown]], by the [[Justin Welby|Archbishop of Canterbury]] on 6 July 2019 in the Private Chapel of [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48891808|title=Harry and Meghan's baby Archie christened at Windsor|date=6 July 2019|last=Dymond|first=Jonny|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nArchie Mountbatten-Windsor is descended from the [[British royal family]] on his father's side and from the American [[American working class|working]] and [[American middle class|middle class]]es on [[Family of Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|his mother's side]].<ref>{{cite news| quote=Doria was born and raised in a middle-class African-American community of Los Angeles. She later earned a master\u2019s degree in social work from the University of Southern California and became a yoga instructor.|last1=Carroll |first1=Leslie |title=How Meghan Markle Was Destined for the Spotlight |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/how-meghan-markle-was-destined-for-the-spotlight |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| quote=She had a pretty American upper middle class existence, including a private elementary and secondary school education and an undergraduate degree from an elite American university.|last1=McFadden |first1=Syreeta |title=Meghan Markle is no modern-day Cinderella. She's better. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/meghan-markle-no-modern-day-cinderella-she-s-better-ncna824596 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Barry\">{{cite news|quote=... he represents change for the oldest of houses. He is half American, descended on his mother\u2019s side from a bellhop in a Cleveland hotel, a laundry worker in Chattanooga, and a bartender in an Atlanta saloon. |last1=Barry |first1=Ellen |last2=Karasz |first2=Palko |title=Meghan, Duchess of Sussex, Gives Birth to a Boy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/06/world/europe/meghan-markle-baby-boy.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> He is a citizen both [[citizen of the United Kingdom|of the United Kingdom]] and [[Citizenship of the United States|of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|title=US tax authorities could stake a claim to Baby Sussex's inheritance|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/07/us-tax-authorities-could-stake-claim-baby-sussexs-inheritance/|first=Harriet|last=Alexander|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=7 May 2019|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news ||title=Royal baby: All you need to know about the birth of Harry and Meghan's child |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47934729 |accessdate=6 May 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Title and succession==\nA great-grandchild of [[Queen Elizabeth II]],<ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/06/meghan-duchess-of-sussex-gives-birth-to-boy|title=Royal baby: Meghan, Duchess of Sussex, gives birth to boy |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 May 2019|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref> Archie Mountbatten-Windsor is seventh in the [[Succession to the British throne|line of succession to the British throne]].<ref name=\"Barry\" /> He is also [[heir apparent]] to his father's [[Dukedom of Sussex]], [[Earl of Dumbarton|Earldom of Dumbarton]], and [[Baron Kilkeel|Barony of Kilkeel]].<ref name=\"guard\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2019/05/06/royal-baby-meghan-markle-birth-boy-latest-live-news-updates/|title=Royal baby: Prince Harry says birth of son is 'the most amazing experience' as world waits for first sighting|last1=Furness|first1=Hannah|date=6 May 2019|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=7 May 2019|last2=Southworth|first2=Phoebe|last3=Herbert|first3=Samantha}}</ref> \n\nAs Harry is not the eldest son of the Prince of Wales, his son is neither a [[British prince]] nor does he have the style Royal Highness. However, if and when Prince Charles becomes King, according to Letters Patent issued by George V in 1917, Harry's son, as the son of the son of the sovereign will have the right to the title of Prince and style of Royal Highness (although there is precedent for titles and styles of this nature to not be used, as in the case of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex#Issue|Prince Edward's children]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Royal Titles: HRH and Prince/Princess |url=https://royalcentral.co.uk/features/history-blogs/history-of-royal-titles-hrh-and-princeprincess-2064/ |website=Royal Central |date=18 May 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> There was the option of using Prince Harry's [[subsidiary title]] of Earl of Dumbarton, as a [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy]], but Meghan and Harry decided instead that he would be styled as [[Master (form of address)#Current usage in the United Kingdom|Master]] Archie Mountbatten-Windsor,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48204592|title=Archie Harrison: The meaning behind the royal baby's name|publisher=[[BBC News]]|first=|last=|date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/succession|title=Succession|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=17 May 2019|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> in accordance with their wish that he grow up as a private citizen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/world/europe/royal-baby-sussex.html|title=Harry and Meghan Name Their Son: Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Ellen|last=Barry|date=8 May 2019 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Archie Harrison Mountbatten-Windsor \u2013 what's in a name? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/08/archie-harrison-mountbatten-windsor-whats-in-a-name-royal-baby |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 May 2019|accessdate=11 May 2019|author= Davies, Caroline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.royal.uk/archie-harrison-mountbatten-windsor Archie Mountbatten-Windsor] at the Royal Family website\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou||6 May|2019|||}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|The Duke of Sussex]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Succession to the British throne]]|years=7th in line}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|The Duke of York]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex}}\n{{Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mountbatten-Windsor, Archie}}\n\n[[Category:2019 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of British descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British people]]\n[[Category:American children]]\n[[Category:British children]]\n[[Category:British people of African-American descent]]\n[[Category:Children of peers and peeresses]]\n[[Category:Markle family]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family|Archie Mountbatten-Windsor]]\n[[Category:People from London]]\n[[Category:Royal children]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8804:1207:9600:196f:570c:9c95:e7d0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archie_Mountbatten-Windsor"}
{"title_page": "Ivana Trump", "text_new": "{{short description|Czech model and entrepreneur}}\n{{distinguish|text=her daughter, [[Ivanka Trump]]}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ivana Trump\n| image              = Ivana Trump cropped retouched.jpg\n| caption            = Trump in 2007\n| birth_name         = Ivana Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1766|2|20}}\n| birth_place        = [[Zl\u00edn|Gottwaldov]], [[Moravia]] [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]]<br />(now [[Zl\u00edn]], [[Czech Republic]])\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Businesswoman\n*model\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Charles University]]\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Alfred Winklmayr|1971|1973|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Donald Trump]]|April 7, 1977|March 22, 1991|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Riccardo Mazzucchelli|1995|1997|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Rossano Rubicondi|2008|2009|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n| children           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Donald Trump Jr.]]\n* [[Ivanka Trump]]\n* [[Eric Trump]]\n}}\n| family             = \n}}\n\n'''Ivana Marie Trump''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1'''; {{IPA-cs|\u02c8z\u025bl\u0272i\u02d0t\u0283kova\u02d0|lang}}, born February 20, 1949) is a Czechoslovakian-born American businesswoman and former model who was the first of the three wives of [[Donald Trump]], the 45th president of the United States. They married in 1977 and divorced in 1991. They have three children together: [[Donald Trump Jr.|Donald Jr.]], [[Ivanka Trump|Ivanka]] and [[Eric Trump|Eric]].\n\n==Early life==\nIvana Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 was born on February 20, 1949 in the [[Moravia]]n town of [[Zl\u00edn]] (formerly known as Gottwaldov), [[Czechoslovakia]], the daughter of Milo\u0161 Zeln\u00ed\u010dek (1927\u20131990) and Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (n\u00e9e Francov\u00e1) (1926-).{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=96}}<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.blesk.cz/clanek/celebrity-ceske-celebrity/572210/extchyne-americkeho-prezidenta-marie-zelnickova-92-ze-zlina-trump-mi-rika-babrle.html |title=Extchyn\u011b americk\u00e9ho prezidenta Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (92) ze Zl\u00edna: Trump mi \u0159\u00edk\u00e1 b\u00e1brle!|website=Blesk.cz|date=October 23, 2018 |access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.myheritage.com/names/marie_zeln%C3%AD%C4%8Dkov%C3%A1 |title=Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (born Francov\u00e1)|website=myheritage.com|access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a56426/ivana-trump-donald-trump-first-wife/ |first=Prachi |last=Gupta |title=6 Things You Need to Know About Donald Trump's First Wife, Ivana |work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] |date=April 8, 2016 |access-date=October 1, 2017 |archive-date=April 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409122704/http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a56426/ivana-trump-donald-trump-first-wife/}}</ref> Milo\u0161 (also born in Zl\u00edn) was an [[engineer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/txfZM|title=DEATHS - The Washington Post|date=2020-03-20|website=archive.is|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> whose family mostly came from urban [[T\u0159eb\u00ed\u010d]] while his maternal grandfather Anton\u00edn Kopeck\u00fd came from [[Bud\u00edkov]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/656/?strana=212|title=Actapublica - Matriky - Moravsk\u00fd zemsk\u00fd archiv Brno|website=actapublica.eu|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:3Q9M-CS72-NHQJ-2?from=lynx1UIV8&treeref=GQTZ-341|title=Czech Republic, Havl\u00ed\u010dk\u016fv Brod, Lipnice nad S\u00e1zavou, Lipnice nad S\u00e1zavou, church records|last=Kopecky|first=|date=1869|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Marie and her family were from [[Velk\u00e9 Pavlovice]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/10155/?strana=45|title=Actapublica - Matriky - Moravsk\u00fd zemsk\u00fd archiv Brno|website=actapublica.eu|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> a daughter from her father's second marriage after his first wife passed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/10155/?strana=8|title=Velk\u00e9 Pavlovice 3610 (Franc's 2 marriages)|last=Franc|first=|date=|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1's family was of [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] heritage.\n\nFrom the age of 13, her father nurtured and encouraged her skiing talent. Before the [[Prague Spring]] of 1968, she was seventeen when she began attending [[Charles University in Prague]] studying [[German language|German]] and [[English language|English]] and continued her education in the early 1970s when she attained a masters degree in physical education.{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=22}}<ref>{{cite magazine| last1 = van Meter| first1 = Johnathan| date = May 1989| title = That's Why the Lady is a Trump| trans-title = | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&q=trump%20master's%20degree&pg=PA86&v=onepage| issn = 0890-1759| magazine = [[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]| publisher = Sussex Publishers, LLC| page = 89 | access-date  = February 9, 2020| via = [[Google Books]] |archive-date=June 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601020608/https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&dq=trump&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=trump&f=false}}</ref> While at Charles University, she was on the ski team and witnessed [[Warsaw Pact]] tanks entering Prague on August 21, 1968, but, the next day, left with the ski team for [[Breuil-Cervinia|Cervinia]] in [[Italy]] for two weeks during the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|Soviet Union led invasion of Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=25-26}} While she was in Italy, she thought about [[Defection|defecting]] from the [[Eastern Bloc]] to [[Western world|the West]] but she did not want her family in Czechoslovakia to undergo suffering if she had defected, so she returned to Prague where she and her boyfriend George planned their escape from behind the [[Iron Curtain]].{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=26-27}}\n\nAccording to Trump, she was selected as an alternate on the Czechoslovak ski team during the [[Czechoslovakia at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972 Winter Olympics]], her specialties being the [[Downhill (ski competition)|downhill]] and [[Slalom skiing|slalom]].<ref name=\"mmw\">{{cite web |last=White|first=Marion M.|url= https://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/0EB528F413ED16AC?p=AWNB |title=Ivana Trump: Hard work, discipline and self-reliance|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=September 26, 1988|access-date=July 19, 2019|archive-date=November 7, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107132556/https://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/0EB528F413ED16AC?p=AWNB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bell |first=B. |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/trumps-article-1.2715780 |title=They met, they saw and they conquered: Donald and Ivana Trump seemed to have it all\" |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |date=February 11, 1990 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Czechoslovakia did not send a ski team to the [[Alpine skiing at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972 Winter Olympics]].<ref name=OfficialReport>{{cite web|title= The XI Olympic Winter Games Sapporo 1972|url=http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1972/orw1972.pdf| publisher= LA84 Foundation| work= Organizing Committee for the XIth Olympic Winter Games| year= 1972| access-date= January 3, 2014}}   (Page 437\u2013438)</ref> In 1989, Petr Pomezn\u00fd, Secretary General of the [[Czech Olympic Committee|Czechoslovak Olympic Committee]], said, \"Who is this Ivana woman, and why do people keep calling us about her? We have searched so many times and have consulted many, many people, and there is no such girl in our records.\"<ref>{{cite magazine\n| last1        = van Meter\n| first1       = Johnathan\n| date         = May 1989\n| title        = That's Why the Lady is a Trump\n| trans-title  = \n| url          = https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&q=Ivana&v=snippet\n| issn         = 0890-1759\n| magazine     = [[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]\n| publisher    = Sussex Publishers, LLC\n| access-date  = June 30, 2013\n| via          = [[Google Books]]\n| archive-date = June 1, 2017\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170601020608/https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&dq=trump&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=trump&f=false\n}}</ref>\n\n==Relationships==\nIn 1971, Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 married Austrian ski instructor Alfred Winklmayr to obtain Austrian citizenship to be able to leave Communist Czechoslovakia without defecting and being therefore unable to return to visit her parents.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Lague\">{{cite news|last=Lague|first=Louise|url = https://people.com/archive/ivana-alone-vol-33-no-11/ |title =Ivana Alone|work =People Magazine| date =March 19, 1990|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"McCauley\">{{cite news|last=McCauley|first=Dana|url = https://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/this-is-the-woman-who-made-donald-trump-a-household-name/news-story/429266fca850e552ef18f66cfd4718f6 |title =This is the woman who made Donald Trump a household name|work =People Magazine| date =May 1, 2016|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite news|last=Gross|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=7PcJmjU_n0UC&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=new+york+magazine+ivana+trump+george+syrovatka#v=onepage&q=new%20york%20magazine%20ivana%20trump%20george%20syrovatka|title=Ivana's New Life|work=New York Magazine|date=October 15, 1990|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> She received her Austrian passport in March 1972<ref name=\"Conconi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1990/02/22/personalities/6416c328-06cb-4efc-817e-03292e68d5a3/|title=PERSONALITIES|first=Chuck|last=Conconi|date=February 22, 1990|publisher=|access-date=November 22, 2017|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> and, as Ivana Winklmayr, in 1973 obtained an absentee divorce from Alfred Winklmayr in Los Angeles, California, where he had moved to teach skiing.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Lague\"/><ref name=\"Conconi\"/> After her then boyfriend [[:cs:Ji%C5%99%C3%AD %C5%A0taidl|George (Ji\u0159i) Staidl]] was killed in a car accident in 1973,{{sfn|Burleigh|2018|p=82}} Ivana moved to Canada where she lived with her father's sister, who ran Costa Line, and her husband, an architect, in [[Toronto]]'s [[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]] for about a year and a half while she studied English and began to model.{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=30-33}} Then, she moved to Montreal for better modeling opportunies and lived with George (Ji\u0159i) Syrovatka whom she had dated since 1967; he had defected to Canada in 1971 and owned a ski boutique in Montreal.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Lague\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=33}} For the following two years, she lived in Montreal, improved her English by taking night courses at [[McGill University]],{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=35}} and worked as a model.<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=33-35}} Her modeling jobs included promoting the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] that were being hosted in [[Montreal]].<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=35}}\n\n[[File:Donald and Ivana Trump.jpg|thumb|upright|Ivana and [[Donald Trump]], 1985]]\nIn this capacity Ivana was in [[New York City]] with a group of models in 1976 where she met [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=39-44}} Donald Trump and Ivana M. Winklmayr were married in 1977 in a lavish wedding officiated by [[Norman Vincent Peale]].{{sfn|Barrett|2016|p=132}}{{sfn|Blair|2015|p=300}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mahler|first1=Jonathan|last2=Flegenheimer|first2=Matt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/21/us/politics/donald-trump-roy-cohn.html|title=What Donald Trump Learned From Joseph McCarthy's Right-Hand Man|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2016|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> Donald and Ivana Trump became leading figures in New York society during the 1980s. They worked on several large projects, including the renovation of the [[Grand Hyatt New York|Grand Hyatt Hotel]] in New York City, construction of the [[Trump Taj Mahal Casino Resort]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], and the [[Trump Tower (New York)|Trump Tower]] on [[Fifth Avenue]] in Manhattan.<ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2015/07/donald-ivana-trump-divorce-prenup-marie-brenner \"After The Gold Rush\"]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''. August 1990. Retrieved January 10, 2016. \"They were married in New York during Easter of 1977. Mayor Beame attended the wedding at Marble Collegiate Church. Donald had already made his alliance with Roy Cohn, who would become his lawyer and mentor.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/08/07/business/the-empire-and-ego-of-donald-trump.html|title=The Empire and Ego of Donald Trump|date=August 7, 1983|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey had three children: [[Donald Trump Jr.]] (born December 31, 1977), [[Ivanka Trump]] (born October 30, 1981), and [[Eric Trump]] (born January 6, 1984). Donald Jr. learned to speak fluent Czech (with the help of his maternal grandfather), while daughter Ivanka has only basic understanding of her mother's native tongue and Eric was not exposed to the language because at the time of his birth his grandparents were already comfortable enough in using English.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ivana Trump Now Fashions Herself As Plaza's Innkeeper|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1989-05-14/features/2690591_1_trump-tower-skis-trump-castle/2|access-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Did Their Father Really Know Best?|work=New York|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/people/features/10610/|access-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref><!-- removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)--> Ivana has ten grandchildren.\n\nIvana took a major role in [[The Trump Organization]]. She became the Vice President of Interior Design for the company, leading the signature design of Trump Tower. Afterwards, her then-husband appointed her to head the [[Trump Castle Hotel and Casino]] as president. She became a naturalized US citizen in 1988.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1899&dat=19880527&id=LiEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YmYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5053,3823442|title=Ivana Trump becomes U.S. citizen|date=May 27, 1988|access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=236}}\n\nIn October 1990, Ivana Trump's 63-year-old father died suddenly from a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. According to [[The Guardian]], her father \u2013 Milo\u0161 Zeln\u00ed\u010dek \u2013 was an informer for Czechoslovakia's [[St\u00e1tn\u00ed bezpe\u010dnost]] (StB) [[intelligence service]] and relayed information from Ivana Trump, including a prediction that [[George H.W. Bush]] would win the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Luke |title='A very different world' \u2013 inside the Czech spying operation on Trump |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/29/czechoslovakia-spied-on-trump-to-exploit-ties-to-highest-echelons-of-us-power |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=29 October 2018}}</ref> Ivana stood side-by-side with her husband Donald at the funeral in [[Zl\u00edn]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Libiger |first1=Milan |last2=\u017delezn\u00edk |first2=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Trumpa p\u0159ivedl do Zl\u00edna tch\u00e1n\u016fv poh\u0159eb, d\u011bti sem jezdily na pr\u00e1zdniny |url=https://www.idnes.cz/zlin/zpravy/donald-trump-byl-ve-zline-synove-vzpominaji-na-prazdniny-u-prarodicu.A161110_2285077_zlin-zpravy_ras |website=iDNES.cz |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=cs |date=2016-11-11 |quote=Father-in-law's funeral brought Trump to Zl\u00edn, his children used to spend holidays there}}</ref> Jaroslav Jansa, codename \"Jarda\" and secret collaborator to the [[St\u00e1tn\u00ed bezpe\u010dnost|StB]] also attended the funeral.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> That Christmas, when the family was on vacation in [[Aspen, Colorado]], Ivana Trump encountered [[Marla Maples]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-02-18/features/9001140529_1_ivana-trump-donald-trump-marla-maples|title=With 'Dynasty' Dead, Just Tune To The Trumps|last1=Lavin|first1=Cheryl|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> who would later become Donald's second wife.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115146/http://articles.philly.com/1993-12-21/news/25943197_1_trump-wedding-marla-maples-richest-man|title=The Donald Bids Hearts For Marla Trump Wedding Draws 1,100 Friends, But Not Many Stars - philly-archives|date=2015-12-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n[[File:Ivana Trump shakes hands with Fahd of Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|left|Ivana met with King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]], 1985]]\n\nThe Trumps' divorce proceedings appeared on New York tabloid newspapers' covers for eleven days in a row, and [[Liz Smith (journalist)|Liz Smith]] wrote about nothing else for three months.<ref name=\"leland20170730\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/nyregion/liz-smith-lions-of-new-york.html |title=Life Among the Boldface Names |last=Leland |first=John |date=July 30, 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 28, 2017 |page=MB1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In a deposition relating to their divorce, she accused Donald J. Trump of rape and of pulling out handfuls of her hair.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/court-docs-reveal-donald-trump-cruel-treatment-ivana-article-1.2796179|title=Court docs reveal Donald Trump's 'cruel' treatment of Ivana|work=NY Daily News|access-date=October 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In [[Harry Hurt III]]'s book ''Lost Tycoon: The Many Lives of Donald J. Trump'', Ivana Trump confirmed that she had \"felt violated\". However, in a statement provided by Donald J. Trump and his lawyers, Ivana Trump stated that she did use the word \"rape\", but that she did not \"want [her] words to be interpreted in a literal or criminal sense.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Their divorce was granted in 1990 on the grounds of \"[c]ruel and inhuman treatment by Mr. Trump\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/12/nyregion/trumps-get-divorce-next-who-gets-what.html|title=Trumps Get Divorce; Next, Who Gets What?|last=|first=|date=|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> A condition of settlement was that she wouldn't talk about their marriage without his permission.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/07/27/ex-wife-donald-trump-made-feel-violated-during-sex | title=Ex-Wife: Donald Trump Made Me Feel 'Violated' During Sex | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | date=July 27, 2015 | accessdate=May 10, 2017 | author=Mak, Tim}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, she married Riccardo Mazzucchelli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20122713,00.html|title=Riccardo, We Hardly Knew Ye : People.com|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> She filed a $15 million breach of contract suit against Mazzucchelli for violating the confidentiality clause in their prenuptial agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/ivana-muzzle-soon-to-be-ex-article-1.771313|title=Ivana wants to muzzle soon-to-be-ex|work=Daily News|location=New York|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In 1997, Mazzucchelli sued Ivana and Donald for libel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/husband-sues-ivana-and-donald-trump-for-libel-1253222.html|title=Husband sues Ivana and Donald Trump for libel|date=July 29, 1997|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1997, she began dating Roffredo Gaetani, which continued until his death in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| last = Wadler| first = Joyce| title = PUBLIC LIVES; Ivana's Boy Toy (for the Record, He's a Prince)| work = The New York Times| accessdate = March 29, 2017| date = March 20, 1998| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/20/nyregion/public-lives-ivana-s-boy-toy-for-the-record-he-s-a-prince.html}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Ivana, then 59, married Rossano Rubicondi, then 36.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marx |first=Linda |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20190959,00.html |title=Ivana Trump Marries for the Fourth Time \u2013 Weddings, Ivana Trump |work=People |accessdate=October 24, 2012}}</ref> The $3 million wedding for 400 guests was hosted by ex-husband Donald Trump at his [[Mar-a-Lago]] estate. Daughter Ivanka Trump was her maid of honor.<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idINN1748314820080417 Ivana Trump weds actor Rossano Rubicondi: report] Reuters</ref> On December 1, 2008, Ivana confirmed to the [[Associated Press]] that she had filed a legal separation agreement three months previously; she has stated in interviews that she and her husband have an [[on-again/off-again relationship]]. In December 2009, she said she had filed for divorce from Rubicondi;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.upi.com/Ivana-Trump-divorcing-husband-Rubicondi/28021261930955/ |title=Ivana Trump divorcing husband Rubicondi |date=December 27, 2009 |access-date=February 24, 2018 |publisher=United Press International }}</ref> the couple has continued to be seen together as recently as May 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/ivana-trump-appeared-on-italian-%e2%80%98dancing-with-the-stars/ar-AAwR3HX?li=BBnbfcL&ocid=U453DHP/ |title=Ivana Trump Appeared On Italian Dancing With The Stars With Ex-Husband Rubicondi}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Business ventures===\nSoon after her divorce from Donald Trump in 1992, she developed lines of clothing, fashion jewelry and beauty products that have been sold through television shopping channels.\n\nIn 2005, Trump was involved in several proposed condominium projects that ultimately failed, including the never-built [[Ivana Las Vegas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Aug-15-Mon-2005/business/2867912.html|title=High-Rise Development: Ivana buys into project|last=Robison|first=Jennifer|date=August 15, 2005|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051029050640/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Aug-15-Mon-2005/business/2867912.html|archive-date=October 29, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Jul-19-Wed-2006/news/8570964.html|title=Pamela, Kid Rock finally to marry|last=Clarke|first=Norm|date=July 19, 2006|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060720221601/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Jul-19-Wed-2006/news/8570964.html|archive-date=July 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, she sued the Finnish fashion company, [[Ivana Helsinki]], accusing it of selling women's clothing that incorporates her name without permission.<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/idINTRE68F4BQ20100916 Ivana Trump sues Finnish designer over name:report] Reuters</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nShe has written several novels, including, ''For Love Alone'' (1992), ''Free to Love'' (1993) and a [[self-help]] book called, ''The Best is Yet to Come: Coping with Divorce and Enjoying Life Again'' (1995).\n\nIn June 1995, she began writing an advice column for ''[[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]'', titled Ask Ivana, about love and life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19950601&id=KHk1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=0-AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3910,149601|title=Ask Ivana|work= [[The Daily Gazette]]|date=June 1, 1995|accessdate= November 28, 2016}}</ref> In 1998, she bought 33% of Croatia's second-largest daily newspaper \u2013 with a circulation of 100,000 \u2013 she used to travel with her parents from the Czech Republic to Croatia on vacation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Successful Beach Polo Premiere in Croatia|url=http://www.poloplus10.com/rovinj-beach-polo-cup-2016-successful-beach-polo-premiere-croatia-65141/|website=POLO+10 The Polo Magazine|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tribune New Services|title=And The Town's Name Rang A Bell With Her|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-22/news/9801220095_1_ivana-trump-donald-trump-croatia|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 22, 1998|language=en}}</ref> In February 1999, she launched her own lifestyle magazine titled ''Ivana's Living in Style''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1999-02-24/lifestyle/9902230731_1_ivana-trump-miniskirt-takeout|title=Picture This: Ivana Has Her Own Magazine|last=White|first=Diane|work= [[Boston Globe]]|date=February 24, 1999|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> In 2001, she contributed an advice column for \"Divorce Magazine\".<ref>Zwecker, Bill, \"Ivana's trump? Divorce column that shares all she's learned\", ''Chicago Sun-Times'', January 24, 2001</ref> In January 2010, Trump ended her advice column in ''[[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]'' to pursue other business interests.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Trump|first= Ivana|date= January 25, 2010|title= Bye, Bye Ivana!|magazine= [[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]|quote=Dear Readers: After years of hard work and devoted service as GLOBE's advice columnist, I regretfully have decided to resign from the position. While I have thoroughly enjoyed being a part of the GLOBE family, as well as the many friendships that I have developed over the years, other business pursuits, both nationally and internationally, will not allow me to devote the attention necessary to the column and to my readers.|page=18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she released an autobiography, ''[[Raising Trump]]'', that covers her own upbringing and the early years of raising her children with [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Gail |author-link=Gail Collins |date=October 12, 2017 |title=The Trumps, the Poodle, the Sex Scandal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/opinion/ivana-ivanka-trump-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 9, 2020 |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209011209/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/opinion/ivana-ivanka-trump-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Trump|first1=Ivana|title=Raising Trump|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gQ5aDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Raising+Trump&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmuNjdo8PnAhWvkHIEHSAYB5EQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=Raising%20Trump&f=false|date=October 2017|publisher=[[Gallery Publishing Group|Gallery Books]]|via=[[Google Books]]|isbn=978-1-5011-7728-6}}</ref>\n\n==Media appearances==\nShe played a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] role in the [[Hollywood]] film ''[[The First Wives Club]]'' (1996) with the line: \"Ladies, you have to be strong and independent. And remember: don't get mad, get everything.\"<ref name=\"Cettl\">{{cite book|last1=Cettl|first1=Robert|title=Film Talk|date=2010|publisher=Wider Screenings|isbn=9780987050038|page=54}}</ref>\n\nShe was the host of [[Oxygen Network]]'s [[dating show|reality-dating program]] ''[[Ivana Young Man]]'', which aired in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peyser|first=Andrea|title=Ivana: Give Me a Stud; Boy-Toy Joy On Her Dating Reality Show|url=https://nypost.com/2006/04/30/ivana-give-me-a-stud-boy-toy-joy-on-her-dating-reality-show/|accessdate=November 29, 2017|work=[[New York Post]]|date=April 30, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she was a [[boardroom]] advisor on ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn 2010, Trump took part in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] version of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 7 (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'', finishing seventh.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n<!--This section is ONLY for books that are cited in footnotes of this Wikipedia article.-->\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title= Trump: The Deals and the Downfall|last=Barrett|first=Wayne|authorlink=Wayne Barrett|publisher=Harper Collins |year=2016 |orig-year=First published 1992|edition= First Regan Art Paperback |isbn= 978-1-682450-79-6 |ref=harv }} ''Paperback title: The greatest show on Earth : The deals, the downfall, the reinvention''\n*{{cite book |title=The Trumps :Three generations that built an empire |last=Blair |first=Gwenda |authorlink=Gwenda Blair |publisher=Simon & Schuster Paperbacks |year=2015 |orig-year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7432-1079-9 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/trumps00gwen }}\n*{{cite book |title=Golden handcuffs : the secret history of trump\u2019s women |last=Burleigh |first=Nina |authorlink=Nina Burleigh|publisher=Gallery Books |year=2018 |orig-year= 2018|isbn= 978-1-5011-8020-0 |ref=harv |title-link=Golden_handcuffs}}\n*{{cite book |title=The lost tycoon : the rise and demise of Donald J. Trump |last=Hurt III|first=Harry |authorlink=Harry Hurt III|publisher=W. W. Norton Company, Inc. |year=1993 |orig-year=First published 1993 |isbn= 0-393-03029-6 |ref=harv |title-link=Lost_Tycoon}}\n*{{cite book |title=Raising Trump |last=Trump |first=Ivana |publisher=[[Gallery Publishing Group|Gallery Books]] |year=September 2017 |orig-year=First published 2017 |isbn=978-1-5011-7728-6 |ref=harv |title-link=Raising_Trump}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ivana Trump}}\n* {{IMDb name | id= 0005506 | name= Ivana Trump }}\n\n{{Trump family}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trump, Ivana}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Moravian descent]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Czech businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Czech female models]]\n[[Category:Czech socialites]]\n[[Category:People from Zl\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Trump family|Ivana]]\n[[Category:Czech women in business]]\n[[Category:Czech expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Czech model and entrepreneur}}\n{{distinguish|text=her daughter, [[Ivanka Trump]]}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ivana Trump\n| image              = Ivana Trump cropped retouched.jpg\n| caption            = Trump in 2007\n| birth_name         = Ivana Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1949|2|20}}\n| birth_place        = [[Zl\u00edn|Gottwaldov]], [[Moravia]] [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]]<br />(now [[Zl\u00edn]], [[Czech Republic]])\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Businesswoman\n*model\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Charles University]]\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Alfred Winklmayr|1971|1973|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Donald Trump]]|April 7, 1977|March 22, 1991|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Riccardo Mazzucchelli|1995|1997|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Rossano Rubicondi|2008|2009|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n| children           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Donald Trump Jr.]]\n* [[Ivanka Trump]]\n* [[Eric Trump]]\n}}\n| family             = \n}}\n\n'''Ivana Marie Trump''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1'''; {{IPA-cs|\u02c8z\u025bl\u0272i\u02d0t\u0283kova\u02d0|lang}}, born February 20, 1949) is a Czechoslovakian-born American businesswoman and former model who was the first of the three wives of [[Donald Trump]], the 45th president of the United States. They married in 1977 and divorced in 1991. They have three children together: [[Donald Trump Jr.|Donald Jr.]], [[Ivanka Trump|Ivanka]] and [[Eric Trump|Eric]].\n\n==Early life==\nIvana Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 was born on February 20, 1949 in the [[Moravia]]n town of [[Zl\u00edn]] (formerly known as Gottwaldov), [[Czechoslovakia]], the daughter of Milo\u0161 Zeln\u00ed\u010dek (1927\u20131990) and Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (n\u00e9e Francov\u00e1) (1926-).{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=96}}<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.blesk.cz/clanek/celebrity-ceske-celebrity/572210/extchyne-americkeho-prezidenta-marie-zelnickova-92-ze-zlina-trump-mi-rika-babrle.html |title=Extchyn\u011b americk\u00e9ho prezidenta Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (92) ze Zl\u00edna: Trump mi \u0159\u00edk\u00e1 b\u00e1brle!|website=Blesk.cz|date=October 23, 2018 |access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.myheritage.com/names/marie_zeln%C3%AD%C4%8Dkov%C3%A1 |title=Marie Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 (born Francov\u00e1)|website=myheritage.com|access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a56426/ivana-trump-donald-trump-first-wife/ |first=Prachi |last=Gupta |title=6 Things You Need to Know About Donald Trump's First Wife, Ivana |work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] |date=April 8, 2016 |access-date=October 1, 2017 |archive-date=April 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409122704/http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a56426/ivana-trump-donald-trump-first-wife/}}</ref> Milo\u0161 (also born in Zl\u00edn) was an [[engineer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/txfZM|title=DEATHS - The Washington Post|date=2020-03-20|website=archive.is|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> whose family mostly came from urban [[T\u0159eb\u00ed\u010d]] while his maternal grandfather Anton\u00edn Kopeck\u00fd came from [[Bud\u00edkov]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/656/?strana=212|title=Actapublica - Matriky - Moravsk\u00fd zemsk\u00fd archiv Brno|website=actapublica.eu|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:3Q9M-CS72-NHQJ-2?from=lynx1UIV8&treeref=GQTZ-341|title=Czech Republic, Havl\u00ed\u010dk\u016fv Brod, Lipnice nad S\u00e1zavou, Lipnice nad S\u00e1zavou, church records|last=Kopecky|first=|date=1869|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Marie and her family were from [[Velk\u00e9 Pavlovice]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/10155/?strana=45|title=Actapublica - Matriky - Moravsk\u00fd zemsk\u00fd archiv Brno|website=actapublica.eu|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> a daughter from her father's second marriage after his first wife passed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://actapublica.eu/matriky/brno/prohlizec/10155/?strana=8|title=Velk\u00e9 Pavlovice 3610 (Franc's 2 marriages)|last=Franc|first=|date=|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1's family was of [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] heritage.\n\nFrom the age of 13, her father nurtured and encouraged her skiing talent. Before the [[Prague Spring]] of 1968, she was seventeen when she began attending [[Charles University in Prague]] studying [[German language|German]] and [[English language|English]] and continued her education in the early 1970s when she attained a masters degree in physical education.{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=22}}<ref>{{cite magazine| last1 = van Meter| first1 = Johnathan| date = May 1989| title = That's Why the Lady is a Trump| trans-title = | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&q=trump%20master's%20degree&pg=PA86&v=onepage| issn = 0890-1759| magazine = [[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]| publisher = Sussex Publishers, LLC| page = 89 | access-date  = February 9, 2020| via = [[Google Books]] |archive-date=June 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601020608/https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&dq=trump&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=trump&f=false}}</ref> While at Charles University, she was on the ski team and witnessed [[Warsaw Pact]] tanks entering Prague on August 21, 1968, but, the next day, left with the ski team for [[Breuil-Cervinia|Cervinia]] in [[Italy]] for two weeks during the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|Soviet Union led invasion of Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=25-26}} While she was in Italy, she thought about [[Defection|defecting]] from the [[Eastern Bloc]] to [[Western world|the West]] but she did not want her family in Czechoslovakia to undergo suffering if she had defected, so she returned to Prague where she and her boyfriend George planned their escape from behind the [[Iron Curtain]].{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=26-27}}\n\nAccording to Trump, she was selected as an alternate on the Czechoslovak ski team during the [[Czechoslovakia at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972 Winter Olympics]], her specialties being the [[Downhill (ski competition)|downhill]] and [[Slalom skiing|slalom]].<ref name=\"mmw\">{{cite web |last=White|first=Marion M.|url= https://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/0EB528F413ED16AC?p=AWNB |title=Ivana Trump: Hard work, discipline and self-reliance|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=September 26, 1988|access-date=July 19, 2019|archive-date=November 7, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107132556/https://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/0EB528F413ED16AC?p=AWNB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bell |first=B. |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/trumps-article-1.2715780 |title=They met, they saw and they conquered: Donald and Ivana Trump seemed to have it all\" |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |date=February 11, 1990 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Czechoslovakia did not send a ski team to the [[Alpine skiing at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972 Winter Olympics]].<ref name=OfficialReport>{{cite web|title= The XI Olympic Winter Games Sapporo 1972|url=http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1972/orw1972.pdf| publisher= LA84 Foundation| work= Organizing Committee for the XIth Olympic Winter Games| year= 1972| access-date= January 3, 2014}}   (Page 437\u2013438)</ref> In 1989, Petr Pomezn\u00fd, Secretary General of the [[Czech Olympic Committee|Czechoslovak Olympic Committee]], said, \"Who is this Ivana woman, and why do people keep calling us about her? We have searched so many times and have consulted many, many people, and there is no such girl in our records.\"<ref>{{cite magazine\n| last1        = van Meter\n| first1       = Johnathan\n| date         = May 1989\n| title        = That's Why the Lady is a Trump\n| trans-title  = \n| url          = https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&q=Ivana&v=snippet\n| issn         = 0890-1759\n| magazine     = [[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]\n| publisher    = Sussex Publishers, LLC\n| access-date  = June 30, 2013\n| via          = [[Google Books]]\n| archive-date = June 1, 2017\n| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170601020608/https://books.google.com/books?id=xaCC4gI-zJkC&lpg=PA98&dq=trump&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=trump&f=false\n}}</ref>\n\n==Relationships==\nIn 1971, Zeln\u00ed\u010dkov\u00e1 married Austrian ski instructor Alfred Winklmayr to obtain Austrian citizenship to be able to leave Communist Czechoslovakia without defecting and being therefore unable to return to visit her parents.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Lague\">{{cite news|last=Lague|first=Louise|url = https://people.com/archive/ivana-alone-vol-33-no-11/ |title =Ivana Alone|work =People Magazine| date =March 19, 1990|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"McCauley\">{{cite news|last=McCauley|first=Dana|url = https://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/this-is-the-woman-who-made-donald-trump-a-household-name/news-story/429266fca850e552ef18f66cfd4718f6 |title =This is the woman who made Donald Trump a household name|work =People Magazine| date =May 1, 2016|access-date=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite news|last=Gross|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=7PcJmjU_n0UC&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=new+york+magazine+ivana+trump+george+syrovatka#v=onepage&q=new%20york%20magazine%20ivana%20trump%20george%20syrovatka|title=Ivana's New Life|work=New York Magazine|date=October 15, 1990|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> She received her Austrian passport in March 1972<ref name=\"Conconi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1990/02/22/personalities/6416c328-06cb-4efc-817e-03292e68d5a3/|title=PERSONALITIES|first=Chuck|last=Conconi|date=February 22, 1990|publisher=|access-date=November 22, 2017|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> and, as Ivana Winklmayr, in 1973 obtained an absentee divorce from Alfred Winklmayr in Los Angeles, California, where he had moved to teach skiing.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Lague\"/><ref name=\"Conconi\"/> After her then boyfriend [[:cs:Ji%C5%99%C3%AD %C5%A0taidl|George (Ji\u0159i) Staidl]] was killed in a car accident in 1973,{{sfn|Burleigh|2018|p=82}} Ivana moved to Canada where she lived with her father's sister, who ran Costa Line, and her husband, an architect, in [[Toronto]]'s [[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]] for about a year and a half while she studied English and began to model.{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=30-33}} Then, she moved to Montreal for better modeling opportunies and lived with George (Ji\u0159i) Syrovatka whom she had dated since 1967; he had defected to Canada in 1971 and owned a ski boutique in Montreal.{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=99}}<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Lague\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=33}} For the following two years, she lived in Montreal, improved her English by taking night courses at [[McGill University]],{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=35}} and worked as a model.<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=33-35}} Her modeling jobs included promoting the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] that were being hosted in [[Montreal]].<ref name=\"Gupta\"/><ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=35}}\n\n[[File:Donald and Ivana Trump.jpg|thumb|upright|Ivana and [[Donald Trump]], 1985]]\nIn this capacity Ivana was in [[New York City]] with a group of models in 1976 where she met [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"Gross\"/>{{sfn|Trump|2017|pp=39-44}} Donald Trump and Ivana M. Winklmayr were married in 1977 in a lavish wedding officiated by [[Norman Vincent Peale]].{{sfn|Barrett|2016|p=132}}{{sfn|Blair|2015|p=300}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mahler|first1=Jonathan|last2=Flegenheimer|first2=Matt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/21/us/politics/donald-trump-roy-cohn.html|title=What Donald Trump Learned From Joseph McCarthy's Right-Hand Man|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 20, 2016|access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> Donald and Ivana Trump became leading figures in New York society during the 1980s. They worked on several large projects, including the renovation of the [[Grand Hyatt New York|Grand Hyatt Hotel]] in New York City, construction of the [[Trump Taj Mahal Casino Resort]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], and the [[Trump Tower (New York)|Trump Tower]] on [[Fifth Avenue]] in Manhattan.<ref>[http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2015/07/donald-ivana-trump-divorce-prenup-marie-brenner \"After The Gold Rush\"]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''. August 1990. Retrieved January 10, 2016. \"They were married in New York during Easter of 1977. Mayor Beame attended the wedding at Marble Collegiate Church. Donald had already made his alliance with Roy Cohn, who would become his lawyer and mentor.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/08/07/business/the-empire-and-ego-of-donald-trump.html|title=The Empire and Ego of Donald Trump|date=August 7, 1983|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey had three children: [[Donald Trump Jr.]] (born December 31, 1977), [[Ivanka Trump]] (born October 30, 1981), and [[Eric Trump]] (born January 6, 1984). Donald Jr. learned to speak fluent Czech (with the help of his maternal grandfather), while daughter Ivanka has only basic understanding of her mother's native tongue and Eric was not exposed to the language because at the time of his birth his grandparents were already comfortable enough in using English.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ivana Trump Now Fashions Herself As Plaza's Innkeeper|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1989-05-14/features/2690591_1_trump-tower-skis-trump-castle/2|access-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Did Their Father Really Know Best?|work=New York|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/people/features/10610/|access-date=August 11, 2016}}</ref><!-- removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)--> Ivana has ten grandchildren.\n\nIvana took a major role in [[The Trump Organization]]. She became the Vice President of Interior Design for the company, leading the signature design of Trump Tower. Afterwards, her then-husband appointed her to head the [[Trump Castle Hotel and Casino]] as president. She became a naturalized US citizen in 1988.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1899&dat=19880527&id=LiEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YmYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5053,3823442|title=Ivana Trump becomes U.S. citizen|date=May 27, 1988|access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Hurt III|1993|p=236}}\n\nIn October 1990, Ivana Trump's 63-year-old father died suddenly from a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. According to [[The Guardian]], her father \u2013 Milo\u0161 Zeln\u00ed\u010dek \u2013 was an informer for Czechoslovakia's [[St\u00e1tn\u00ed bezpe\u010dnost]] (StB) [[intelligence service]] and relayed information from Ivana Trump, including a prediction that [[George H.W. Bush]] would win the [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential election]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Luke |title='A very different world' \u2013 inside the Czech spying operation on Trump |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/29/czechoslovakia-spied-on-trump-to-exploit-ties-to-highest-echelons-of-us-power |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=29 October 2018}}</ref> Ivana stood side-by-side with her husband Donald at the funeral in [[Zl\u00edn]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Libiger |first1=Milan |last2=\u017delezn\u00edk |first2=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Trumpa p\u0159ivedl do Zl\u00edna tch\u00e1n\u016fv poh\u0159eb, d\u011bti sem jezdily na pr\u00e1zdniny |url=https://www.idnes.cz/zlin/zpravy/donald-trump-byl-ve-zline-synove-vzpominaji-na-prazdniny-u-prarodicu.A161110_2285077_zlin-zpravy_ras |website=iDNES.cz |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=cs |date=2016-11-11 |quote=Father-in-law's funeral brought Trump to Zl\u00edn, his children used to spend holidays there}}</ref> Jaroslav Jansa, codename \"Jarda\" and secret collaborator to the [[St\u00e1tn\u00ed bezpe\u010dnost|StB]] also attended the funeral.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> That Christmas, when the family was on vacation in [[Aspen, Colorado]], Ivana Trump encountered [[Marla Maples]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-02-18/features/9001140529_1_ivana-trump-donald-trump-marla-maples|title=With 'Dynasty' Dead, Just Tune To The Trumps|last1=Lavin|first1=Cheryl|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> who would later become Donald's second wife.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115146/http://articles.philly.com/1993-12-21/news/25943197_1_trump-wedding-marla-maples-richest-man|title=The Donald Bids Hearts For Marla Trump Wedding Draws 1,100 Friends, But Not Many Stars - philly-archives|date=2015-12-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n[[File:Ivana Trump shakes hands with Fahd of Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|left|Ivana met with King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]], 1985]]\n\nThe Trumps' divorce proceedings appeared on New York tabloid newspapers' covers for eleven days in a row, and [[Liz Smith (journalist)|Liz Smith]] wrote about nothing else for three months.<ref name=\"leland20170730\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/nyregion/liz-smith-lions-of-new-york.html |title=Life Among the Boldface Names |last=Leland |first=John |date=July 30, 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=July 28, 2017 |page=MB1 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In a deposition relating to their divorce, she accused Donald J. Trump of rape and of pulling out handfuls of her hair.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/court-docs-reveal-donald-trump-cruel-treatment-ivana-article-1.2796179|title=Court docs reveal Donald Trump's 'cruel' treatment of Ivana|work=NY Daily News|access-date=October 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In [[Harry Hurt III]]'s book ''Lost Tycoon: The Many Lives of Donald J. Trump'', Ivana Trump confirmed that she had \"felt violated\". However, in a statement provided by Donald J. Trump and his lawyers, Ivana Trump stated that she did use the word \"rape\", but that she did not \"want [her] words to be interpreted in a literal or criminal sense.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Their divorce was granted in 1990 on the grounds of \"[c]ruel and inhuman treatment by Mr. Trump\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/12/nyregion/trumps-get-divorce-next-who-gets-what.html|title=Trumps Get Divorce; Next, Who Gets What?|last=|first=|date=|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> A condition of settlement was that she wouldn't talk about their marriage without his permission.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/07/27/ex-wife-donald-trump-made-feel-violated-during-sex | title=Ex-Wife: Donald Trump Made Me Feel 'Violated' During Sex | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | date=July 27, 2015 | accessdate=May 10, 2017 | author=Mak, Tim}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, she married Riccardo Mazzucchelli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20122713,00.html|title=Riccardo, We Hardly Knew Ye : People.com|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> She filed a $15 million breach of contract suit against Mazzucchelli for violating the confidentiality clause in their prenuptial agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/ivana-muzzle-soon-to-be-ex-article-1.771313|title=Ivana wants to muzzle soon-to-be-ex|work=Daily News|location=New York|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In 1997, Mazzucchelli sued Ivana and Donald for libel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/husband-sues-ivana-and-donald-trump-for-libel-1253222.html|title=Husband sues Ivana and Donald Trump for libel|date=July 29, 1997|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1997, she began dating Roffredo Gaetani, which continued until his death in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| last = Wadler| first = Joyce| title = PUBLIC LIVES; Ivana's Boy Toy (for the Record, He's a Prince)| work = The New York Times| accessdate = March 29, 2017| date = March 20, 1998| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/20/nyregion/public-lives-ivana-s-boy-toy-for-the-record-he-s-a-prince.html}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Ivana, then 59, married Rossano Rubicondi, then 36.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marx |first=Linda |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20190959,00.html |title=Ivana Trump Marries for the Fourth Time \u2013 Weddings, Ivana Trump |work=People |accessdate=October 24, 2012}}</ref> The $3 million wedding for 400 guests was hosted by ex-husband Donald Trump at his [[Mar-a-Lago]] estate. Daughter Ivanka Trump was her maid of honor.<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idINN1748314820080417 Ivana Trump weds actor Rossano Rubicondi: report] Reuters</ref> On December 1, 2008, Ivana confirmed to the [[Associated Press]] that she had filed a legal separation agreement three months previously; she has stated in interviews that she and her husband have an [[on-again/off-again relationship]]. In December 2009, she said she had filed for divorce from Rubicondi;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.upi.com/Ivana-Trump-divorcing-husband-Rubicondi/28021261930955/ |title=Ivana Trump divorcing husband Rubicondi |date=December 27, 2009 |access-date=February 24, 2018 |publisher=United Press International }}</ref> the couple has continued to be seen together as recently as May 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/ivana-trump-appeared-on-italian-%e2%80%98dancing-with-the-stars/ar-AAwR3HX?li=BBnbfcL&ocid=U453DHP/ |title=Ivana Trump Appeared On Italian Dancing With The Stars With Ex-Husband Rubicondi}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Business ventures===\nSoon after her divorce from Donald Trump in 1992, she developed lines of clothing, fashion jewelry and beauty products that have been sold through television shopping channels.\n\nIn 2005, Trump was involved in several proposed condominium projects that ultimately failed, including the never-built [[Ivana Las Vegas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Aug-15-Mon-2005/business/2867912.html|title=High-Rise Development: Ivana buys into project|last=Robison|first=Jennifer|date=August 15, 2005|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051029050640/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Aug-15-Mon-2005/business/2867912.html|archive-date=October 29, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Jul-19-Wed-2006/news/8570964.html|title=Pamela, Kid Rock finally to marry|last=Clarke|first=Norm|date=July 19, 2006|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060720221601/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Jul-19-Wed-2006/news/8570964.html|archive-date=July 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, she sued the Finnish fashion company, [[Ivana Helsinki]], accusing it of selling women's clothing that incorporates her name without permission.<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/idINTRE68F4BQ20100916 Ivana Trump sues Finnish designer over name:report] Reuters</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nShe has written several novels, including, ''For Love Alone'' (1992), ''Free to Love'' (1993) and a [[self-help]] book called, ''The Best is Yet to Come: Coping with Divorce and Enjoying Life Again'' (1995).\n\nIn June 1995, she began writing an advice column for ''[[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]'', titled Ask Ivana, about love and life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19950601&id=KHk1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=0-AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3910,149601|title=Ask Ivana|work= [[The Daily Gazette]]|date=June 1, 1995|accessdate= November 28, 2016}}</ref> In 1998, she bought 33% of Croatia's second-largest daily newspaper \u2013 with a circulation of 100,000 \u2013 she used to travel with her parents from the Czech Republic to Croatia on vacation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Successful Beach Polo Premiere in Croatia|url=http://www.poloplus10.com/rovinj-beach-polo-cup-2016-successful-beach-polo-premiere-croatia-65141/|website=POLO+10 The Polo Magazine|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tribune New Services|title=And The Town's Name Rang A Bell With Her|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-22/news/9801220095_1_ivana-trump-donald-trump-croatia|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 22, 1998|language=en}}</ref> In February 1999, she launched her own lifestyle magazine titled ''Ivana's Living in Style''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1999-02-24/lifestyle/9902230731_1_ivana-trump-miniskirt-takeout|title=Picture This: Ivana Has Her Own Magazine|last=White|first=Diane|work= [[Boston Globe]]|date=February 24, 1999|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> In 2001, she contributed an advice column for \"Divorce Magazine\".<ref>Zwecker, Bill, \"Ivana's trump? Divorce column that shares all she's learned\", ''Chicago Sun-Times'', January 24, 2001</ref> In January 2010, Trump ended her advice column in ''[[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]'' to pursue other business interests.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Trump|first= Ivana|date= January 25, 2010|title= Bye, Bye Ivana!|magazine= [[Globe (tabloid)|Globe]]|quote=Dear Readers: After years of hard work and devoted service as GLOBE's advice columnist, I regretfully have decided to resign from the position. While I have thoroughly enjoyed being a part of the GLOBE family, as well as the many friendships that I have developed over the years, other business pursuits, both nationally and internationally, will not allow me to devote the attention necessary to the column and to my readers.|page=18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she released an autobiography, ''[[Raising Trump]]'', that covers her own upbringing and the early years of raising her children with [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Gail |author-link=Gail Collins |date=October 12, 2017 |title=The Trumps, the Poodle, the Sex Scandal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/opinion/ivana-ivanka-trump-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 9, 2020 |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209011209/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/opinion/ivana-ivanka-trump-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Trump|first1=Ivana|title=Raising Trump|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gQ5aDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Raising+Trump&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmuNjdo8PnAhWvkHIEHSAYB5EQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=Raising%20Trump&f=false|date=October 2017|publisher=[[Gallery Publishing Group|Gallery Books]]|via=[[Google Books]]|isbn=978-1-5011-7728-6}}</ref>\n\n==Media appearances==\nShe played a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] role in the [[Hollywood]] film ''[[The First Wives Club]]'' (1996) with the line: \"Ladies, you have to be strong and independent. And remember: don't get mad, get everything.\"<ref name=\"Cettl\">{{cite book|last1=Cettl|first1=Robert|title=Film Talk|date=2010|publisher=Wider Screenings|isbn=9780987050038|page=54}}</ref>\n\nShe was the host of [[Oxygen Network]]'s [[dating show|reality-dating program]] ''[[Ivana Young Man]]'', which aired in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peyser|first=Andrea|title=Ivana: Give Me a Stud; Boy-Toy Joy On Her Dating Reality Show|url=https://nypost.com/2006/04/30/ivana-give-me-a-stud-boy-toy-joy-on-her-dating-reality-show/|accessdate=November 29, 2017|work=[[New York Post]]|date=April 30, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, she was a [[boardroom]] advisor on ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn 2010, Trump took part in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] version of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 7 (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'', finishing seventh.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n<!--This section is ONLY for books that are cited in footnotes of this Wikipedia article.-->\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title= Trump: The Deals and the Downfall|last=Barrett|first=Wayne|authorlink=Wayne Barrett|publisher=Harper Collins |year=2016 |orig-year=First published 1992|edition= First Regan Art Paperback |isbn= 978-1-682450-79-6 |ref=harv }} ''Paperback title: The greatest show on Earth : The deals, the downfall, the reinvention''\n*{{cite book |title=The Trumps :Three generations that built an empire |last=Blair |first=Gwenda |authorlink=Gwenda Blair |publisher=Simon & Schuster Paperbacks |year=2015 |orig-year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7432-1079-9 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/trumps00gwen }}\n*{{cite book |title=Golden handcuffs : the secret history of trump\u2019s women |last=Burleigh |first=Nina |authorlink=Nina Burleigh|publisher=Gallery Books |year=2018 |orig-year= 2018|isbn= 978-1-5011-8020-0 |ref=harv |title-link=Golden_handcuffs}}\n*{{cite book |title=The lost tycoon : the rise and demise of Donald J. Trump |last=Hurt III|first=Harry |authorlink=Harry Hurt III|publisher=W. W. Norton Company, Inc. |year=1993 |orig-year=First published 1993 |isbn= 0-393-03029-6 |ref=harv |title-link=Lost_Tycoon}}\n*{{cite book |title=Raising Trump |last=Trump |first=Ivana |publisher=[[Gallery Publishing Group|Gallery Books]] |year=September 2017 |orig-year=First published 2017 |isbn=978-1-5011-7728-6 |ref=harv |title-link=Raising_Trump}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ivana Trump}}\n* {{IMDb name | id= 0005506 | name= Ivana Trump }}\n\n{{Trump family}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trump, Ivana}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Moravian descent]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Czech businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Czech female models]]\n[[Category:Czech socialites]]\n[[Category:People from Zl\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Trump family|Ivana]]\n[[Category:Czech women in business]]\n[[Category:Czech expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n", "name_user": "Gamerbob2625", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivana_Trump"}
